\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6383048\charrsid6383048 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14244499 Could you begin by telling me when and where you were born?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6383048\charrsid6383048 COLIN:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14244499 Yes.  I was born in 1942.  I\rquote m a War Baby, which means, though I was born in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Enfield{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} in Middlesex, it\rquote s utterly irrelevant to the rest of my life!  My parents were Londoners from either side of the River, and met at work in a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid15552741 n insurance office.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14244499 My father was an insurance clerk, and my mother was a secretary.  He was at war \endash  fought in, partly in North Africa, but it was then in West Africa \endash 
 none of this, of course, it\rquote s all hindsight, they\rquote re the things I know, although, curiously, my earliest actual memory that I can date is of VE Day Celebrations in Bury St. Edmunds, of all strange places, because that\rquote 
s where my father was then stationed.  But my father, in 1946, moved out \endash  classic Londoner, moved out to Tunbridge Wells, and commuted back in \endash  and we always continued to think of ourselves as Londoners, like I supported London Football
 Clubs.  My mother didn\rquote t work in paid employment, as one would now say, and my father commuted back in as an aspiring insurance clerk, to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Central London{\*\xmlclose}
, which meant I hardly saw him, except at weekends, because he was out of the door before I was up, and frequently was back after I was in bed.  I have a younger brother and a younger sister, and my brother is two years younger, and my sister i}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15552741 s five years younger than me.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14244499 I think the most defining thing about me, maybe full stop the defining thing about m
e, is that my father died when I was 12, of a cerebral haemorrhage, and so unexpectedly, in every sense of the word, we are fatherless, my mother\rquote 
s widowed.  And we were living in rented accommodation, always had lived in rented accommodation owned by my father\rquote s employer, a big insurance company \endash  Liverpool Victoria Insurance Company, in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
Central London{\*\xmlclose}.  And I would say that, socially and economically, you know, we were skidders at this point, we were going downstream fast, and certainly my dominant memory of my childhood, teenagehood really, is o}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15552741 f having no money whatsoever.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14244499 
Go back one stage, my father, clearly, was very aspiring, tremendous pressure on the 11+. And I passed the 11+, and I was the only one - my brother and sister both failed \endash  and went t
o the local grammar school, which then, as now, is a very distinguished, in the league table sense, school, it\rquote s called the Judd School in Tonbridge, and it\rquote 
s a classic small town grammar school that was an offshoot of a major public school, there\rquote s a majo
r public school in Tonbridge, which was irrelevant to my life in Tunbridge [Wells].  But I went to Judd which continues to be, along with, you know, the Colchester schools, and the Tunbridge Wells High School, and all the rest of it, it\rquote 
s in that sort of top ten of those sort of schools \endash  I didn\rquote t know it was that good, of course.  And it was, and is, a very good academic school, with the classic assumption that the best people will go to Oxbridge and so on.  And it\rquote 
s full, I now realise, of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} public servants, full of very Senior Civil Servants\rquote 
 children, who commute up from Tunbridge on a very good railway line.  And school, I now know \endash  this is hindsight \endash  I was quite bright, and my performance at school goes down, markedly, after my father died.  The
 School was highly streamed, but they kept me in the top stream, but I was regularly in the bottom of the top stream, but never went down, and I think that was the School being rather kind to me. 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6383048\charrsid6383048 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14244499 Were they supportive to you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6383048\charrsid6383048 COLIN:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14244499 Yeah, I think so.  I think so.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6383048\charrsid6383048 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14244499 And were there particular teachers who were important to you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6383048\charrsid6383048 COLIN:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14244499 
Not early on.  Later on, certainly, two or three teachers were terribly important to me, particularly a geography master called Whitehouse, who certainly influence
d me enormously.  I was very interested in geography and I wanted to go to university to do geography.  But I wasn\rquote 
t, I then discovered, well enough looked after. Because it was clear the only two things I was any good at were probably going to be history and geography, and, in fact, I finished up doing history, geography and English Literature as \lquote A\rquote 
 level.  But if you want to read history, or wanted to read history in the early sixties, I left school in 1960, you had to have \lquote O\rquote  level Latin, nobody would take you in without \lquote O\rquote  level - and I\rquote 
d managed to avoid doing any Latin, just about.  And if you wanted to do geography, in that period, you almost invariably required an \lquote A\rquote  level science.  This was the time when universities were still matriculating you
 very much to disciplines.  But what I spotted, and I think it was me, was that what became Keele, but then University College of North Staffordshire, matriculated you \endash  these are terms I would use now \endash 
 to the University, and you could get in to the University on any \lquote A\rquote  levels, and then read the subject of your choice.  That is now the normal pattern, but it was very unusual pre the Robbins Universities.  But it wasn\rquote t \'85 let
\rquote s go back a bit.  I\rquote m a classic kind of fourth former, or fifth former, was thinking I was going to leave school at 16, when large numbers of people, even from Judd, left at 16, and I wasn\rquote t performing terribly well \'85
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6383048\charrsid6383048 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14244499 And was that partly economics? 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6383048\charrsid6383048 COLIN:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14244499 Yeah, I think so, and I felt the need to go to work.  I felt the need to
 go to work, and I was persuaded, I think by my mother, rather than the School, to stay on after \lquote O\rquote  levels. My \lquote O\rquote  levels were average, you know, I got six or seven \lquote O\rquote  levels \endash  we\rquote 
re not talking about spectacular performance in anything like this.  And also, the School \'85 I think, really, if you were going to Oxbridge that was fine, or maybe law at University College or something like that, but anything else didn\rquote 
t really matter, and it was just prior to the great expansion of universities, five or six per cent of the age group was going to university in 1960, if that, so, you know, I wasn\rquote 
t really expected to be there.  And partly because of Geography (with a capital G), I decided that I was going to go and work for a shipping agent in the City of London, 
and a very famous firm, which has now been taken over, called Killick Martin, offered me a job at 17.  I was going to leave school at 17, and I was going to start in this shipping agent.  And partly, I think, because of a girlfriend I then had, I decided 
that I wouldn\rquote t \'85 I mean, I\rquote d left school, but then came back into the Upper Sixth, having decid}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15552741 ed that I would try and go on. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14244499 
There were two things, I think. It was the first time I became really successful at school, I was in the middle mass of very bright people and I would guess, I don\rquote t think it\rquote 
s an excuse, I would guess I was probably under-performing, partly because of the domestic situation.  I mean, throughout the time I was there I had paper rounds, I worked on milk rounds, I did a bit of meat on Saturday mornings \endash 
 unusual for people at Judd \endash  and that was partly because I was not taking pocket money, or money, off my mother, and I was working in a way which is now very familiar to \'85 I mean, young people do this all the time, but it wasn\rquote t as usua
l at that time.  And then in the Upper Sixth, I decided I was going to go to university, and worked rather hard, and got - I don\rquote t know whether, then, they were letters or numbers, but A\rquote s or 1\rquote 
s in history and geography, and something like }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15552741 3 or C in English Literature.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14244499 But also, I had started to be rather adventurous, in every sense of the word 
\endash  not in terms of sex and drugs and rock and roll, particularly \endash  but I, I was very curious about the place, and a friend of mine, who has actually recently died, 
he and I, as 17-year olds, in the summer of 1959, between Lower and Upper Sixth, hitch-hiked to Land\rquote s End from Tunbridge Wells, at a time when people didn\rquote 
t do that kind of thing.  And the School being a sort of upper end grammar school, was interested in things that public schools did, including having a membership of something called \'93The British Schools Exploring Society\'94, which used to be called 
\'93The British Public Schools Exploring Society\'94, which went on expeditions to very adventurous places.  And I
 decided I would try and go on one of these. The school had only managed to get one person in ten years on these things - it was competitive, you were interviewed and all that sort of stuff - and I was chosen, and it meant that I suddenly became famous at
 school.  And I went to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Iceland{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 between school and university, partly because I really wanted to become a physical geographer. I was very interested in glaciers and volcanoes, and you can do both of those in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
country-region}}Iceland{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. And I think, for the first time, I had a kind of sense of being able to do th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15552741 ings, a sense of achievement.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14244499 
I don\rquote t think I was really rebelling against the School, and I can actually - it\rquote s interesting, in terms of my politics later, I can remember being surprised that there were people at this
 School who were not voting Conservative.  I was surprised that they were not voting Conservative in the 1959 Election, and I was actually rather surprised about this.  And so I had no feeling of being on the Left or Labour, or whatever, that all came - t
hat was what Keele did to me.  I wasn\rquote t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15552741  associated with any of that.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14244499 I think I got, from the School, support.  It\rquote 
s very interesting, I can give you interesting documentation.  My sister has recently given me a pile of correspondence associated with going to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Iceland{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose}, because it was assumed there was going to be parental subsidy, and it was going to cost \'a3200 - which was beyond one\rquote 
s wildest imaginings in 1959.  And my sister gave me this pile of correspondence, because my mother has relatively recently died
, and it shows the School, unbeknown to me, was massively supportive in raising the money. The School is an adjunct to the Skinners Company, Livery Company, in London, because Judd was a Skinner in the 17}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\super\insrsid14244499 th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14244499  century, and the School, to my amazement, there w
ere good letters from the Headmaster to my mother, saying where the money could be found, and how it would go and support the Local Authority, and money from the Local Authority. None of that, if I knew it I\rquote 
ve forgotten it, but I think I never knew it, because I would have said that the School didn\rquote t like me, and what\rquote s more, I didn\rquote t like them, and I wasn\rquote 
t terribly keen on it.  And there was no way of really being rebellious. This is pre real teenagedom, there was no long hair. But I }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15552741 wasn\rquote t starkly hostile to it.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14244499 I\rquote m very very struck by the similarities in attitude to the School that I discovered in Tom Courtney\rquote s book, a book called }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid14244499 Dear Tom}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14244499 , which is these letters to his mother.  Now, he\rquote s very working-class, he\rquote s the son of a ship\rquote s painter.  I couldn\rquote t claim anything like that, we were declining lower middle-class, but I\rquote 
ll say some more about that in a minute.  And his attitude to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Kingston{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Grammar School{\*\xmlclose} \endash  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\ul\insrsid14244499 the}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14244499  Grammar School in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Hull{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} \endash 
 was a bit like mine, he was slightly surprised to be a success, and didn\rquote t like it terribly much, he k}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15552741 new he wasn\rquote t really of that.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14244499 
Given that I used to get my students at Edinburgh to write [family] autobiographical stuff, I ought to go back and say that [my] grandparents are quite \'85 Classic British kinship, I can\rquote t get much back beyond that.  My father\rquote 
s father was a unionised {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}South London{\*\xmlclose} gas meter reader, and could talk about Will Thorne and people like that.  Autodidact, reader of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid14244499 The Times}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14244499 .  And my father, unexpectedly, I think, for their times, went to Alleyn\rquote s Co
llege, which has the same relationship to Dulwich, coincidentally, as Judd has to Tonbridge.  My father left at 16, and went into the insurance office, but he had - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14244499\charrsid12084115 I}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14244499  have, I don\rquote t think they would have taught me this, a very strong conception of my father
 being upwardly mobile, out of the working-class.  And very difficult for me, in later years, I mean as a young person, to really engage much with my paternal grandparents, because they were shadows of their former selves \endash 
 my mother used that phrase.  They\rquote d been bombed out in the Second World War, and she \endash  my father\rquote s mother \endash 
 had been terribly terribly injured, massively fractured skull, blinded, and I only remember her as an invalid.  And he, my grandfather \endash  my father\rquote s father \endash  was, I think, understa
ndably, bitter and twisted.  He felt, very much, that people who had been bombed out should get Council houses, but they never had got enough points, at a time of acute housing shortage.  They had lost all their possessions in the bombing, I don\rquote 
t know whe
ther you got anything through insurance, but they were living in rather impoverished circumstances, and I used to hate visiting them very much.  And then, of course, the poor bastards, my father had a brother, who I never knew, who died of meningitis, yon
ks ago, I don\rquote 
t even know when, so they have their one son who then dies before them as well, and I just remember them as, without being condescending, rather pathetic.  She was pathetic, and very difficult, cross with the world, and blind, and he was rathe
r bitter with the cards he had been dealt \'85
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6383048\charrsid6383048 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14244499 So you don\rquote t think those ideas that he would have had as a trade unionist, would have had any influence? 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6383048\charrsid6383048 COLIN:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14244499 I think I identified with them later on, I actually understood what that was about, later on, but I didn\rquote 
t at the time.  My father also, I knew he was different to other people, because he read }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid14244499 The Times}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14244499 
, and that was odd for people of his class, but it was more to do with it being a proper serious read, than being a member of the upper classes.
  And he kept press-cuttings, and the house was full of scrap books of rather boring things.  Indeed, on my shelves, curiously, there\rquote s a Beveridge, which was his, from 1944 \endash  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid14244499 
The Full Employment in a Free Society}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14244499 .  And I think I was beginning to take that in. The other thing I got from him was jazz, because he used to listen to jazz on the radio, and I\rquote 
ve still got that, absolutely, and I\rquote m sure that\rquote s where that came from.  
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6383048\charrsid6383048 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14244499 But what about, as a person, then, your father?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6383048\charrsid6383048 COLIN:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14244499 Well, I remember h
im as an obsessive reader, which is probably important.  He was always known as someone with four or five books under his arm, which is what he did while he was on the train.  I think we would have fought like hell!  I would have thought there would have 
been all \'85 Because, I mean, I kick over the traces, but I didn\rquote t work terribly hard at school, I don\rquote t think I would have got away with that.  Had he been alive, I think he would have really driven me, and I think I\rquote 
d have probably rebelled.  He was, I know, very anxious about what I would now think of as the upward mobility saga.  I mean, I remember him, I mean, \'93with affection\'94 is the wrong word, it\rquote 
s quite difficult to retrace the emotions, even now, when it\rquote s \'85  So down as 12, a devastating thing to happen to you, and totally unexpected.  It wasn\rquote t as if he was ill. He literally, I\rquote 
d been with him to a rugby match at the School, and I\rquote d gone on my bike, and I rode home, and he was going to go home on the bus, and he died on the bus.  And never came \'85 We w
aited for him till the police came round.  And so it was utterly devastating.  And I think, in a way, it\rquote 
s got more to do with, not just, you know, absolutely the loss and all that, but I think the real fear, what was going to happen to us?  There is no money.  And I think it\rquote s had probably all sorts \'85 I mean, I don\rquote t think I\rquote 
