\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14244499  was very influential on me.  And if you\rquote re gossiping, actively gossiping, as part of inarticulate creating of solidarity, you do swap information. Frequently they are actually quite interested \'85
 people are quite interested in knowing.  You could want to know about, I don\rquote t know, other Sociology Departments that I\rquote ve worked in, because you have a reason that I don\rquote 
t know, for wanting to know about that Sociology Department. So you\rquote ll tell me something, so I\rquote ll ask }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15552741 you something, about whatever. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14244499 
I found I could gain enormous amounts by telling people things that I probably - I mean, I don\rquote t think it was ever, you know, either salacious or particularly damaging, or probably even terribly confidential.  They just wonder, \'93
What does he really do?\'94  \'93Oh\'94, I said, \'93You know, he\rquote s just a Director of so and so\'94.  \'93Oh!\'94  And I caught a frisson, a couple of times, of where you realised you shouldn\rquote t \'85
 You know, you feel lack of authenticity in yourself, but also a realisation that they might not want to tell you that, actually, his job\rquote s not this, but his job\rquote s that, or whatever. Or he\rquote s had a bad time at work and he\rquote 
s got sacked from that, but he did that. Which is quite an important thing for me to know, but they won\rquote t tell you because }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15552741 you might tell somebody else.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14244499 I think, partly because I was beginning to develop an understanding of fieldwork, that I became a lot more conscious that I needed to understand what I was doing, and of what the role consisted. That it you\rquote re not a mate, you
