 paper by Daniel Bertaux, yes, before it was in the book.  I read an English translation.  I was very impressed by it and the petit bourgeois stuff in the class structure. They went on, later, to do landlords and other people in the class str
ucture, in Edinburgh. So I knew of that work.  These were intellectual and social and professional intimates of mine.  And of Howard\rquote s. And we would always see each other at BSA Meetings.  Ray was on the periphery of this \endash  
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PersonName}}Ray Pahl{\*\xmlclose}, Uncle Ray - he wasn\rquote t really central to this, he would come occasionally, but he wasn\rquote 
t really locked into this sort of stuff.  And it is important, though, to know that I, at some time in one of these early years, I taught Ray\rquote s Urban Course in Kent, and commuted from Colchest
er to Canterbury one day a week.  And in that class, in that urban class, was one Pete Saunders, as an undergraduate, and that\rquote 
s how, eventually, I recruited Pete.  So we got this money, we advertised for these posts, and the two people who were appointed were David Rose and Pete Saunders. Pete then had an incomplete Ph.D., which became, eventually, his book, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid8917117 Urban Politics}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117  - around which is a very interesting story. Because, originally, it was going to be called }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid8917117 Short of Corrupt}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 , but he couldn\rquote t get anybody to publish it as }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid8917117 Short of Corrupt}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 
.  David Rose had gone from Cambridge to Bangor \endash  people forget that \endash  and we hired him from Bangor, where he had a Lectureship at Bangor.  They became the Research Officers on the Farmers Project.  The division of labour
 on the Farmers Project was also tangled by the fact - which might relate to other things and we might put down on tape - you know, the beginning of Bell\rquote 
s thrust for power. Because I was also, I was Head of Department at Essex in my penultimate year \endash  \rquote 73 to \lquote 74 \endash  and refused to do the last year after the Chair debacle, when you, me and [Stan] - just you and me didn\rquote 
t get the Chairs, and Stan did  And I did mind Stan getting it. But I wasn\rquote t prepared to be Head of Department, with all these other - at that
 time, it seemed to me utterly unreasonable. And I behaved utterly unreasonably by stamping my foot and refusing to go on, and, of course, going to Australia.  The division of labour was tangled by this, to the extent that I wasn\rquote 
t expected to do much fieldwork whilst I was Head of Department.  And I certainly didn\rquote 
t live away, which the other two did, from time to time, and that also caused, more than - other than Howard, all of us, other than Howard, had got quite complex personal relationships, and their
 marriages broke up, mine did - but nothing to do with the farmers\rquote 
 work - but theirs, in part, some of the stresses and strains of being mobile research workers, with babies. They all had children, and it was far from straightforward.  But the division of
 labour was that Dave ran the survey.  We were going to interview, formally, every other farmer \endash  not going to, we achieved \endash 
 we set out to interview every other farmer who owned over a thousand acres in the four East Anglian counties.  Because if it\rquote s ove
r a thousand acres you can exclude the Fens and one or two other places.  And that was what we set out to do, and we got about 78 per cent, or something like this.  David ran the survey.  Howard loomed over it a bit larger.  Pete did the political work 
\endash  \'93Who runs East Anglia?\'94 \endash  which meant he did loads of work within that community power paradigm, which was also in his }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid8917117 Urban Politics}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 
 book.  We would look both at the expenditure on rates, they spent a lot on police and roads and not much on schools, you co
uld actually see that kind of thing in East Anglia.  But he did loads of interviews with political activists, conventional political activists, and people who were Chairs of County Councils and those sorts of things \endash 
 about what they thought they were up to.
