No, not as far as I know.  Not as far as I know.  Though we all did loads of observation on farms. I mean, none of us worked on them, but you spent so much time with these people, and so on.  And when I ceased to be Head
 of Department, which would have been in the summer of \rquote 74, I was given back, as it were, my share of the interviews to do!  (LAUGHS)  They said, \'93Right, you\rquote re no longer Head of Department!\'94
  And I interviewed, I did the bulk of the interviews in Essex, and so I did loads of work, including people like Richard Butler \endash  RAB Butler\rquote s son \endash 
I did loads of good interviews, I mean, for me, good interviews, around Saffron Walden and that neck of the woods, because the farms tended to be up towards \'85 And that was 
very good, I can still remember them as very powerful experiences, and saw the different sorts of people \endash 
 people who had taken out no hedges, and were self-rated squires and all this kind of stuff.  You know the joke about self-rated?  In the big methodological debate in the early seventies, about how you would get at people\rquote 
s class position.  All those stupid questions about, \'93Some people say, the workforce is like a football team, and we all play on the same side\'94, but you have to say, \'93If you had to [choose]\'85?\'94  And one of the paradigms is, \'93If you }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \ul\insrsid8917117 had}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117  to say you were one of the following, what would you say?\'94 having wittered all this through, and people eventually grudgingly saying, \'93Middle class
\'94, \'93Working class\'94. And we had this wonderful guy, we gave him the list, and he looked at it, and he said, \'93None of those.  I\rquote m a squire\'94!  (LAUGHS)  So we had this thing about \'93self-rated squire\'94 \endash 
 in terms of the language of the farmers!  And I saw they were self-rated squires!  I did interview a guy who was se
lf-rated as a squire, but another guy, who drove a Ferrari, had only three workers.  The squire had something like 24.  The guy with only three workers was farming more.  No nonsense about belonging to Unions, at either end of the spectrum.  But one only 
h
ad three, they were paid very well, they were terribly responsible, they just got on with all the stuff, and are pulling loads of money out, and they knew what they were taking out money for, because he was buying property elsewhere.  The squire was maint
aining a style of life and all that.  They were almost adjacent to each other, so you could actually see them, and no geographic determinism.  So we did all that.  
