\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 COLIN:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 Oh yes, you\rquote 
d literally, sometimes I would ask to see lots of things, they would take you round and they would show you things, and you would walk round with them.  I\rquote ve interviewed o
n a combine harvester (LAUGHS), I was taking notes bouncing down the field!  They take you into the house, you sit in the kitchen.  There\rquote s not, in many of these farms, nothing very dramatic, because arable farms aren\rquote t dramatic, there
\rquote s no cows, and the speed of change isn\rquote t all that great.  But they would stand and talk to you, and talk you through the history of the landscape and things like this.  Some of them were very into it, they\rquote d show you where they
\rquote d pulled the trees down and things like that.  And so it was doing fieldwork.  Classically, the survey was an excuse to be }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid8917117 in situ}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 
, you know, you had a reason for being in somebody\rquote s house, which you wouldn\rquote t otherwise have had, although you write down the answers and all the rest of it.  The actual questions are at the back end of the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\insrsid8917117 Property, Paternalism and Power}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117  book, the questionnaire, the questions are there.We were, also, not uninfluenced by someone who\rquote s important in your life, and that\rquote 
s George Ewart-Evans.  And, you know, I think we might have known about George through you, and through what you were doing, but I\rquote ve been to his house, I\rquote ve got a copy of one of the last books, which wasn\rquote 
t terribly good, inscribed to me, just as we were going to Australia.  I wanted }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid8917117 Property, Paternalism and Power}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 
 to be dedicated to him, but by then I was in Australia and they forgot my desires. I wanted the book to be dedicated to him.  I think though, very early on, as I arrived in Essex, Blythe\rquote s }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid8917117 Akenfield
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117  was published, and I knew it was crap, right from - I 
knew it was kind of a literary imagination of what was going on.  I just somehow knew, through its lack of authenticity as a sociological reading, I couldn\rquote t make it make sense.  And I also went to, I was moving slightly \endash 
 you must have been at some of these meetings, early Oral History meetings, there was a History Meeting held in Leicester, and all sorts of wild and wonderful people were active.  I remember Jill Shankleman, Diana Leonard \'85
