\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 COLIN:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 Slightly more outgoing.  Slightly more outgoing.  I don\rquote t think Howard\rquote s changed all that much in the time that I
\rquote ve known him.  I\rquote m just astonished, absolutely astonished, by his achievements.  And success has not spoilt Howard Newby.  He\rquote s stayed much the same.  I don\rquote t think I\rquote 
m actually the best person to ask, because his relationship with me has been absolutely consistent for - how long have I known him?  Thirty-four years.  The last time I spent any time with him was last summer, and it was exactly the same.  And there
\rquote s nothing wrong with it, absolutely straightforward.  We value each other\rquote s friendship, I 
could pick him up and he would tell me, pick up the phone to him, and he would tell me things, and similarly, I would do it the other way round, I suppose.  And he clearly - I suppose I\rquote 
m guilty of underestimating how able he is, which goes back to what I said about him being an undergraduate, this guy does seem to have the most astonishing capacity for doing new jobs. For example \endash  he\rquote 
s saved the ESRC.  He got Southampton.  I think Howard also, if Howard\rquote s changed at all, he\rquote s become an effective father.  He\rquote 
s got two nice sons.  I think going to America was quite interesting for Howard.  Howard got on to the American circuit by, rather boringly \endash 
 not purposefully - rather boringly, going to meetings of the European Rural Sociology Society.  Rural Sociology is not institutionalised in Britain at all, but it\rquote s bigger in Europe and it\rquote s bigger in America \endash  there\rquote 
s a field called Rural Sociology, and people proudly call themselves - and Howard started to go to these meetings.  I think it\rquote s a bit like joining a sect, they were so pleased to find a new member who wasn\rquote 
t stupid, he promptly became something like Secretary of the European Rural Sociology Society and started organising these meetings.  I\rquote ve been to meetings that Howard\rquote s organised in Rome, and Cordov
a.  Howard was on the Executive of all this, which meant the American Rural Sociology Society found Howard.  It was run from Madison, from the Ag. School, and famous agricultural sociologists, who are only famous in Agricultural Sociology, in America, tho
u
ght Howard, rightly, was an amazing find.  They then offered him a sabbatical position in the Ag. - well, visiting position in the Ag. School. And the rest is history. Howard then found there are, actually, quite a lot of amazing people there, including B
urawoy and Erik Olin Wright, and all the rest of it, which were unknown to us Brits, we didn\rquote t know those people, who those people were.  And, of course, eventually, Erik Olin Wright was very influential on the Marshall, Newby and Rose, }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid8917117 Class in Britain}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 , which is, in part, one of its justifications was an application of Erik Olin Wright\rquote s model \endash  to Britain.  It\rquote 
