s work that compares with, say, Stan on torture, or Stan on Mods and Rockers.  There\rquote s nothing there like that.  And without saying, this is astonishing.  I\rquote m not saying I\rquote ve got anything better, but, you know, the brickwork, there
\rquote s a lot of it.  Classic Newby publication, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid8917117 Current Sociology}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117  on recent literature on stratification \endash  unknown to the bulk of the world \endash 
 big fat }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid8917117 Current Sociology}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117  - absolutely valuable.  He also wrote an ESRC Report on the State of the World, on social stratification.  Again,
 not many people know that he did this.  Nothing\rquote s missed, but it doesn\rquote t add anything.  You know, there isn\rquote t - what you want is a few more mistakes. Backtracking, Lockwood was incredibly important in, during the whole of that 
\rquote 68 to \rquote 75.  I left in \rquote 75.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 You\rquote ve said about him as an intellectual influence, but what about on the research side?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 COLIN:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 
Oh, because he was there, and because he would talk to you, and we did drag the stuff in to him to talk to him about it.  I think our intellectual respe
ct for him was boundless.  One would never have said that of Peter.  I mean, my respect for Peter, now, is considerably higher than it was then.  My political respect for Peter was always very high, but I never had great intellectual respect for Peter.  I
 have greater intellectual respect now, and I think what he\rquote s done is very significant.  But at the time, you know, I was a brash young man.  But Lockwood \'85!  I wasn\rquote 
t in awe of him, and he was always very nice.  He was responsible for me getting a Senior Lectureship in my third year there, and I was astonished.  I mean, onwards and upwards, but I didn\rquote 
t expect to get that Senior Lectureship, and I would say that that\rquote s as significant a promotion/appointment - well, I mean, I think the only thing I put like it, really, is getting the Chair at Edinburgh.  That\rquote 
s the only thing.  The Senior Lectureship at Essex, and the Chair at Edinburgh are the two things - I even count getting a Vice-Chancellorship as neither here nor there, I think getting the Chair at Edin
burgh was a really really significant achievement. I know what the competition was, and Lockwood was on the Committee, by the way.  So isn\rquote t that fascinating.  Lockwood was on the Committee when I got the Senior Lectureship, and I\rquote 
ve just remembered that Lockwood and Richard Brown were the Externals when I got the Chair at Edinburgh.  But they\rquote re the two things which I would say that, I rest my case, I can do it on a good day.  The others, I think it\rquote 
s chance.  But Lockwood.  For example, I think our best paper on the kind of history of ideas and community, is called something like \'93Class, Community and Communion \endash  Social Sources of Urban Action\'94, and it\rquote 
s actually in a geography reader, it\rquote s quite a good paper.  Lockwood told me about this piece in the Parson\rquote s Reader, by Schmalenbach, on, called, \'93Communion, a Sociological Category\'94
.  It was Lockwood who told me about that piece, and it was, there he was, this kind of endless - and engaged with you. I mean, all father figures, you never know whether they re
ally love you.  You never got anything that much back from David, but I was always immensely appreciative that he was there, and I think the stratification stuff - I mean, I never, was never as appreciative of the Durkheimian stuff.  His great works that 
he\rquote s published since, I don\rquote t like that as much as the whole }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid8917117 Affluent Worker}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 , and the whole }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid8917117 
The Black-Coated Worker}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117  and that kind of stuff.  And the fact that he had read all of the sociological theory and could talk to you about those kind of things.  He p
ersuaded me, and it was very good for me, when he was Head of Department, to teach Sociology of Religion, and I taught Sociology of Religion as an Honours option, in a probably overly empiricist way, but it got me into a vast literature I wouldn\rquote 
t otherwise have known.  I got to teach Christel Lane, as an undergraduate, which I probably wouldn\rquote t have done otherwise.  I knew Christel very well because she was a colleague\rquote 
s wife and so on, but it meant that Christel and I have had a different sort of relation
ship forever, because we got into the Sociology of Religion together.  And David was endlessly helpful.  When I agreed to do it, I mean, he almost, I got a sort of year long tutorial on the Sociology of Religion.  And I realised he really ought to have be
en doing the Sociology of Religion, he just knew it all!  And that was terribly good for me.  That goes back to things I might have said on the earlier tape, about the lack of a sociological education.  And, somehow, maybe that\rquote 
s what I was getting out of David.  And the rest, I think we were self-taught, we did it together, Newby and Saunders, and to a certain extent, you know, even other people up and down the corridor \endash  Adrian [Sinfield].
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 You haven\rquote t characterised Pete or David.  I wonder whether you could? 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid9991740 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 COLIN:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 
Oh yes.  Pete has gone off in all sorts of - we now always refer to him as \'93Crazy Pete\'94, because he\rquote s gone off in all sorts of weird and wonderful directions!  Pete was very very very bright.  He was politically very astute.  I don\rquote 
t mea
n in interpersonal politics, but he somehow understood political nuances.  He got into what I thought was actually a fairly complicated Political Sociology literature very well.  A tremendous person to be with, and tremendous - God!  And sharp as a razor,
 he always - I saw Pete give a paper when I was back from Australia once, it was in somewhere like Nottingham, at an Urban Sociology Conference, and I thought he was just brilliant.  It\rquote s published in Mike Harloe\rquote s journal, the }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid8917117 Journal of Urban and Regional Research}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 
.  David [Rose], then as now, pretty reliable most of the time, solid, got on with it, amiable enough.  I loved him dearly, but we wanted a guy to run the survey, and there was our boy.  I\rquote m being rude and cruel, but that was what it was.  And Dav
id was also going through one of his many tempestuous marriages, as far as I can see, and, therefore, was often distracted from a lot of this. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9991740  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 
Yes.  I used to, honestly, have notions of a fantasy Sociology Department. Other people have fantasy football te
ams.  You know, would W.G. Grace really open, Grace and Hutton to start with, or whatever!  What was your fantasy, what would be my fantasy Department?  And I can remember, and particularly when I was at Aston, I used to think about what it would actually
 
be.  But it did start earlier than that, partly, I suppose being in Australia, because I was so pissed off with how few good sociologists there were in Australia.  But Pete would have always been, Howard would have been in it, Pete would have been in it, 
Harry Collins would have been in it, Christel Lane would have been in it, and Max Atkinson would have been in it.  And you\rquote d have to say, \'93What year Max Atkinson?\'94 and \'93What year Christel Lane?\'94
 (LAUGHS).  But just as you would with Grace and Hutton, you don\rquote t have to actually specify what year.  Pete, I would have always had. I\rquote ve loved some of the things that Pete\rquote s done since, though thinking he\rquote 
s very wrong-headed.  I suppose I, constitutionally, as a person, find it difficult, intellectually, to cope with people who have gone off to the Right, and Pete\rquote 
s gone off to the Right, and has got interested in things which I cannot get on with.  He\rquote s got interested in the influence of biology, the influence of Darwinianism, it all seems to be crypto-Right-wing stuff, and he\rquote 
s in love with the market, and his extreme individualistic version.  And he\rquote s got pamphlets published by the Institute of Economic Affairs.  I\rquote ve just sort of lost it, I\rquote 
ve lost the plot somewhere along the line, while still liking him very much. David, as far as I can see, has achieved quite a lot at the top end of the engine room of the big cohort studies.  And that, in a way, almost looks predictable, but it\rquote 
s wonderful that that has happened.  And at the time, you\rquote ve got to remember, these 
were started as Research Officers.  I was a Senior Lecturer, but Howard was only a Lecturer, and I think the structural opportunity for all of us was just very different.  The system just - the fact that our two people get proper jobs in proper institutio
ns, and then would go on and upwards and so on. Other people that I was looking after at the time, include Graham Allen, for example, who\rquote 
s Ph.D. I was supervising, and then got a job at Southampton, now at Keele, who also got out of the door at the [time].
  They all got good jobs at a time where, not only if you got them, you also then went up quite quickly.  So it must be tough on the people who have come after us.  But not uninteresting.  We were very consciously, over-consciously, sociologists in opposi
tion to all this Social Policy nonsense.  Now, you always had this kind of ambivalent role.  And Adrian [Sinfield] and I used to fight a bit about it.  Adrian, I shouldn\rquote t put this on tape \'85 Adrian\rquote 
s actually coming to supper with us next Saturday, so it\rquote ll be quite interesting, I shall tell him I was interviewed by you!  (LAUGHS)
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid8917117 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 But you stayed as mates, really?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 COLIN:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 Oh yeah, because he\rquote s a Professor across the street, he\rquote s Professor of Social Policy, now Emeritus.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 So why do you see a conflict between sociology and social policy?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 COLIN:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 
Oh, I think it had got to do with weirdnesses about pure and applied knowledge.  I think we were pure sociologists.  We prioritised, Lockwood was our boy, whereas Peter represented a kind of - I don\rquote t know, 
grubby utilitarian policy-led stuff.  Utterly wrongly! I mean, I now vastly appreciate Peter\rquote s work.  But at the time, you know, I was on Alasdair MacIntyre\rquote s side, \'93Old and alone and nasty!\'94
  (LAUGHS) This was what I heard Alasdair say once!  And that was very very unfair.  I think, at the time, I was very young, very na\'efve, I didn\rquote 
t recognise that some of this was actually about power struggles in the Department.  I think, in a very na\'efve sort of way, I thought it was real.  It was whether you identified with sociology or social policy, it wasn\rquote 
t about who came out on top of power struggles.  Although, as I told you, I thought Peter is one of the few people who overtly outmanoeuvred me in meetings, because I suddenly realised he worked at it, whereas, I\rquote d make it up as I went along.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 He was very tenacious.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 COLIN:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 Oh!  Never give it up. He\rquote d always come back at you, whereas my boredom threshold was such that I - \'93Who gives a stuff!  I
\rquote m not going to do this again!\'94  Whereas Peter would be back at you!  Yes, absolutely!  And so you\rquote d have to use words like \'93principled\'94, although at times, I didn\rquote t think he was at all principled.  But \'93principled\'94
, he knows where he\rquote s going to go, and all the rest of it.  I mean, we always used to wonder whether Peter an
d David ever talked to each other.  In fact, they have an amazingly high regard for each other.  And at your [conference], when we were down for Soc. Info., and sat around afterwards \'85
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 Oh yes.  For \'93Celebrating Classic Sociology\'94.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 COLIN:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 Yeah, when
 we were in the tent, David grabbed Peter, and walked him off to talk to him, they went off to talk to each other, because, obviously, they probably hadn\rquote 
t spoken to each other for decades, for all I know.  But they were, instantly, just wanted to - and I thought that was lovely.  I thought that was really really good, and nice to see.  I\rquote 
d like to know what they were talking about!  But for a long time, for me, don\rquote t let\rquote s talk about Essex, the word \'93Department\'94 only meant the Essex Department, and for me, it was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \ul\insrsid8917117 the}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117  most significant socialising experience.  I identified with the place.  And therefore, it wasn\rquote t that I didn\rquote t want to go, I mean, I felt I couldn\rquote t - I didn\rquote 
t want to stay in those \'85  Man in a hurry.  And I was very pissed off about the whole of that, as
 no doubt you were, about the whole Chair business. I thought the Department was buggered around and all the rest of it.  But I knew nothing about the running of the University, and it would have been lunatic to think that you should give people like me m
ore kind of power and authority.  It was crazy that I was Head of Department in \rquote 
73. When you think of the troubles, I mean, there was full-scale occupations and so on, and bloody Noel Annan coming down to write reviews and all the rest of it, as well as pe
ople in the Department, were really really awkward, politically awkward persons, who were actually causing a lot of trouble at that stage \endash  Ted Benton, Mick [Mann] \endash 
 these were people who were organising for all sorts of weird and wonderful reasons.  I suppose what happened after I went, and I\rquote 
ve talked to people about this, somehow the University got slightly more serious, and people like Townsend, came back in to run things.  I went through a period in the seventies where none of the senior people in the 
University, in our neck of the woods, was running anything, and we were just - what an opportunity!  I did the admissions for all of Comparative Studies for about three years.  If you ever want to know about Progressive Access Policy, you should have seen
 the kind of things we used to do!  It didn\rquote t bear - I mean, people like the famous Henry Friedman, I admitted, and so on.  He was one of mine!  (LAUGHS) Those kind of things were absolutely extraordinary.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 Can I ask you one other thing, though?  One of the big changes from \rquote 68 on, was the Women\rquote 
s Movement and Gender.  How did that affect your thinking in sociology?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 COLIN:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 Oh yes, good.  Good.  Good.  I had to transfer - I went there, I was hired, in part, to teach Family and Kinship, and that course 
got transformed by the whole of the gender critique.  Well the first wave of Feminism, post Germaine Greer, I suppose, and to the extent that I almost, I think, by the end, I\rquote 
d given up teaching it, because of worries about the appropriateness of blokes teaching these kind of things.  I don\rquote 
t know how sympathetic I was, intellectually, but I was struggling to build some of that stuff into what we were doing, and I talked a lot - I mean, to friends, people like Di Barker, as she then was, Diana Leonard, and 
also Leonore [Davidoff].  We talked a lot.  I read the manuscript of Leonore\rquote 
s book on servants, for example, before it was out.  And I think I was, I would have said that I was actually quite influenced. Of course, there is the famous paper on marriage th
at Howard and I wrote, where we spotted that this deferential structure that Howard first wrote about in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid8917117 Comparative Studies in Society and History}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 
, that we could apply that.  We were two of the very few blokes who went to the famous 1974 Conference in Abe
rdeen, which was the first Gender Conference of the BSA, where very few blokes went to it.  Very few people went at all, because it was in Aberdeen, and that was somewhere the other side of Adelaide, as far as most people were concerned! Howard and I did 
go to that, and gave that paper, and it is a good paper, and it survived the republication of the Conference Volumes when they went down to just a single volume, so, clearly, the trade liked them.  I think the paper\rquote 
s actually too clever by half, and whether we really meant it or not. I suppose we must, by the standards of some people, have been thought to have been taking this stuff rather seriously.  I knew the Feminists were there, for God\rquote 
s sake, and yeah, I would have thought that it was pretty damned influential.  I\rquote m trying to think of other people who would have - I mean, I\rquote d got out before.  You see, Mary MacIntosh wasn\rquote 
t there when I was there, and the women who were on the staff, included milder persons like Jane Marceau.  Alison MacEwan Scott didn\rquote 
t have much influence.  She was there in the early days, then she buggered off to Latin America for a great chunk of the time of my heyday there, although I\rquote ve got on knowing [her now] she\rquote 
s come back.  Leonore was a very very marginal figure, very out of it, really.  It\rquote s interesting, it doesn\rquote t loom as large as I would have expected it to, with hindsight.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117  So did it change your thoughts on kinship, would you say?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 COLIN:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 Oh, I think it changed my views on whether I could write on the family in qui
te the same way.  I wrote the review, a review article of Willmott and Young\rquote s }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid8917117 Symmetrical Family}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 , for }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid8917117 
Sociology}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 , which I would have said was a sort of Feminist critique of that, and I wrote that before I left - could I have written it before I left Essex?  I think I probably did write it before.  When }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid8917117 The Symmetrical Family}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 
 came out, I opposed the views in that as being rather orthodox and male-centric.  I think I began to realise from, for example, Frankenberg\rquote s piece that\rquote s in the same thing as the \'93Deferential Dialectic\'94
, that you could re-read all this stuff, you could re-read all your earlier stuff, and other people\rquote s work, from a Feminist point of view. I think I was beginning to try and write women back in.  It paid a lot greater dividends later, whe
n I was back from Oz, and working in Aston, and working with people like Malcolm Cross, to a certain extent John Rex, and the people who were working on, in the Race and Ethnic Relations field, particularly in the Race and Ethnic Relations Unit, and worki
ng out what a powerful white bloke would be doing working on black people. I worked out, then, about how you can own these kind of problems, and it\rquote 
s the problems of the powerful, rather than the problems of the powerless.  And I think I managed, later \endash  I don\rquote t think I achieved it at Essex \endash 
 to get a kind of coalescence of views that I feel comfortable with, on things like institutional sexism and institutional racism, and why it\rquote s my problem and not their problem, and why you can actually see how the pract
ices you condone lead to those kind of outcomes.  Which is actually quite important in terms of being a head of an institution, by the way. I don\rquote 
t think I had that, those views whilst - I was as confused as everybody else was, at the time.  I was aware, a
bsolutely, that all the social mobility studies were about blokes.  And I probably was in print saying so.  I knew that Glass, through the whole Blau and Duncan stuff, was all about the male occupational structure, and about movement up and down it.  And 
I began to worry, in an intellectual sense, about - and indeed, the deferential dialectic does go on about - what is the unit of stratification?  If it\rquote 
s the household, it ignores stratification within the household, and maldistribution of resources within the household.  I think I knew that.  And I had a relatively early interest in - did that come from Diana?  It might have done \endash 
 Barker/Leonard \endash  on food and eating, and diet, and what that said about power and influence within.  I think I was probably pretty susceptible to that. I used to organise the BSA\rquote 
s Family and Kinship Study Group.  That was, in effect, taken over by women\rquote s issues, and by the women, and that Study Group died, and only a lot later did any kind of family and kinship stuff, because th
e whole tidal wave of an interest in here, was dominated by Feminist sociology.  I, only later, worried about things like Feminist epistemology, like whether women see things better, as opposed to differently, the kind of things you can find in bits of mi
d-period Anne Oakley.  Oh, I\rquote m responsible for Anne Oakley\rquote s }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid8917117 Occupation Housewife}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 
, and her other book that came out almost at the same time, being two books, because Allen Lane sent me the manuscript to comment on, and I said, \'93It\rquote s not one book, it\rquote s two books.  You should do this one there, and this one there\'94
.  And it became two books.  I don\rquote t think Anne Oakley knows that. I said that, and that was the outcome.  Other people may also be equally responsible.  But it was a single manuscript, a very unwield
y thing, and I thought there were two books lurking in there, and it actually became, became two books.  So somebody thought I should read that stuff, at that time.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 And I suppose your later work with Lorna [McKee], that\rquote s gender? 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 COLIN:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 Yeah.  Yeah.  And Lorna was the first.  No one, no one\rquote 
s ever mistaken Howard Newby for a Feminist.  Lorna McKee was a Feminist, overtly Feminist, identified, she would have said that in the first sentence describing herself.  Now, we don\rquote t say we\rquote re Masculinists, b
ut we probably ought to have done, in a way!  (LAUGHS)  But she was a Feminist, and was clearly going to take - and I don\rquote t think this follows from saying, \'93I am a Feminist\'94 - she was going to take women\rquote 
s experience seriously, and this was always going to be a female-oriented study, at a time of male unemployment.  And that helped enormously.  Actually, one of the reasons she wanted to work with me, she said was the \'93Marriage and Deferential Dialectic
\'94 paper, which showed, at least, I had \'93some inkling of an understanding\'94 \endash  her phrase \endash 
  about some of that.   And I, for good or ill, working with Lorna was very good for me.  I really thought it was, thought it was tremendous, and that took me back to other things that I was, I was interested in.  Yeah, I\rquote d 
forgotten all that.  That\rquote s interesting, it doesn\rquote 
t loom as large.  It was more important than debates with Marx or Poulantzas, or the other kind of things that people thought we were on about. I mean, Lockwood was, you know, was the defender, as it were, 
or what we lined up behind.  Because we would have thought of ourselves as kind of neo-Weberians, and that wasn\rquote t easily compatible with an overt Feminist position in the first instance.  It probably ought to have been, but it wasn\rquote 
t.  And I imagine our actual practices were as unconstructed as anybody else\rquote 
s at the time!  I mean, all sorts of ideologically unacceptable behaviour was undoubtedly going on all the time at Essex, and no doubt has continued - and long may it continue!  (LAUGHS)  But, I mean, I do remember some pretty good parties!  (LAUGHS)

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 Now, I think we\rquote ve finished with Essex.  Do you want a little break? 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 COLIN:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 Yeah.  Why don\rquote t we stop.
\par 
