\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 So can we go on to later research.  Let me pick up one thing you said while we were off the air, which was that you didn\rquote 
t feel that sociology in Australia was very advanced when you went there in \rquote 75.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 COLIN:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 Yeah.  Advanced, yeah, in two senses.  After being in a big powerful sociological community, what I said after 
about 18 months in Australia, there was about enough people to make up one good Department.  The trouble in Australia was, there was 14 Sociology Departments, but there was about enough people to make up one good one.  And so I found both within New South
 Wales, and in Australia as a whole, there weren\rquote t many people who were really kind of at it.  They had an over-deferential intellectual view to somewhere called \'93overseas\'94
, and a lack of confidence in developing, not so much Australian ideas, but even Aust
ralian material.   There was hardly enough empirical material to teach a Modern Industrial Society course on Australian material, and it seemed to be slightly crazy to be teaching Glass, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid8917117 
Social Mobility in Britain}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117  in Australia, and so on.  And the absence of, it wasn\rquote 
t funded, there were not many Ph.D.s, there were people who had written quite good secondary - I mean, Sol Ensol, the other Professor there, had written a book on social stratification in Australia, the bulk of which was theory, it was theories
 of stratification, and there was very little Australian data.  And I found this, I thought the theory was mundane, and there wasn\rquote 
t enough data there.  I could also say that Feminism hit Australian social science, before it had any achievements, and Femin
ism swept over the whole of what was there, in a very very powerful and interesting way.  That happened when I was in Oz.  So, chronologically, it\rquote 
s quite interesting, because I was struggling to think of the impact of all of that in Essex.  By the time I was in Australia, which is the back half of the seventies, it was there, powerfully.  You couldn\rquote 
t avoid it, and everyone was a Feminist, almost regardless of gender, and that was particularly true in Sydney, a very kind of powerful experience.  But there was not much good empirical work going on.  I wrote a paper on Housing Classes \endash 
 Rex and Moore type stuff \endash  on Australian material, and some stuff on the Political Economy of Housing, while I was there.  It was very difficult to get newly generated sociolo
gical data, as opposed to secondary sources through Censuses and so on, about ten year categories and those kind of things.  And it was hard to do that.  I didn\rquote 
t really, in all honesty, do much Australian work.  We were finishing the farmers book.  I edited a book, and published a book on Research Methods, with Sol, called, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid8917117 Inside the Whale}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 .  I wrote some housing papers.  We got }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid8917117 Doing Sociological Research}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 
, with Howard, out the door whilst I was in Australia.  That was published when I was in Australia, wh
ich is why Howard had so much difficulty with Margaret, of course, because he had to do the negotiations to keep her happy about all of that.  And after about three years in Oz, when this was coming to an end, I think we\rquote 
d made up our minds I was going to try and come back, and, therefore, I was looking for jobs in Britain, and not making a big intellectual commitment. 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 Why did you want to come back?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 COLIN:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 It was a curious combination of careerism and domesticity.  Jocelyn and I were actually getti
ng on quite well.  There was a small but not powerful issue, I don\rquote t want to exaggerate about Jocelyn\rquote 
s mother, who was on her own, and not terribly terribly well, and so those kind of things.  And there was a bit of an issue, we did discuss, if we stay much longer, we\rquote 
re not going to be able to get the children out.  Does that matter?  And are the children going to become Australian?  And if they won\rquote t come, you know, they were well into teenage, Rachel\rquote s in Sydney Girls\rquote  High School, and if we don
\rquote t move soon, we don\rquote t move.  Does that matter?  We thought it did matter. I had other friends, literally, up and down the street, who were people I\rquote 
d known for many years, with, coincidence, someone I was at Keele with, was two doors down the street, and was in t
he Geography Department in New South Wales, and they, they made the opposite decision and stayed, and their kids are Australian and all the rest of it.  It wasn\rquote t that I didn\rquote 
t want my children to become Australians, but we thought if we didn\rquote t move soon, we were in for the duration.  I would have become an Australian Vice-Chancellor.
