\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 COLIN:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 Mmm.  Yeah.  And also, I think I wanted, still, my real ambition was to be the head of a Si
ngle Honours providing Sociology Department in a reasonable university, and if I could still achieve that, I thought, in the late seventies, that\rquote 
s what I would want to do.  And I had a serious go at it, and I think I knew I was wrong, but I was of the opinion that it didn\rquote t really matter where this Department was, because you could have a great Department in a crap university \endash 
 Essex \endash  and you could build.  Before the \rquote 81 cuts, don\rquote t forget, before the \rquote 81 cuts, you couldn\rquote t anticipate how differentiated the sector might become.  It didn\rquote 
t really matter where you would be.  So I applied for, I was interviewed for two jobs when I was back from Australia, on, I don\rquote t think it was even a sabbatical, I was just back on leave.  I was interviewed for Aston and th
e OU.  I was interviewed along with Stuart Hall.  They\rquote 
d have been crazy to give me the OU.  But Aston also interviewed Duncan Gallie, and they gave Duncan Gallie the job, who eventually turned it down, and they eventually came to me.  So I was their second choice. I thought it didn\rquote 
t matter.  I particularly thought it didn\rquote t matter, because it was made absolutely clear to me that I could make, immediately, two more appointments \endash  one at Senior Lecture level, one at Lectureship level.  And I began to achiev
e the ideal Department, because the lecturer I appointed was Christel Lane, because David was then in Birmingham.  And the Senior Lecturer was a very good guy, who\rquote s still at Aston, called Dennis Smith, who was then at Leicester. I thought it didn
\rquote t matter.  It did matter, because of the July \rquote 
81 cuts, and everything that went on thereafter, which was really very painful stuff.  And the shock of coming back, which really was a shock to the system.  I sort of also defined it, not completely untruthfully, but
 slightly unfairly, as being that Jocelyn wanted to come back more than I did, and that had I only stayed in Australia, where I was clearly going to be the next Dean of the Faculty of Arts in New South Wales.  Deans are kind of - in New South Wales, then,
 as now, are more important than Deans are in some places, I was clearly going to be on the way up, and Deans are semi-permanent and all the rest of it.  And I\rquote 
d got, you know, this crap job in a crap institution, with Keith Joseph shitting on us from a great height.  And I hated, I\rquote ve never warmed to Birmingham, I just didn\rquote t like it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 So you didn\rquote t live there?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 COLIN:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 Oh, lived, we did live there, and I didn\rquote t like it.  Didn\rquote 
t like it at all.  And then, you know, somehow Sir Keith Joseph proved my judgement right, that I shouldn\rquote 
t have been there.  And then for a variety of complex reasons, it was clear I was not going to stay with Jocelyn, and I left, and then went back, and I left again.  And so all of this was kind of immensely complicated.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 And Jan was a student at Aston? 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 COLIN:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 
No, no, she was just on the staff.  On the staff.  Yeah.  And that had nothing to do with me leaving Jocelyn to start with.  I mean, it did eventually, but it had nothing to do with it in the first instance.  I\rquote d be
en away from Jocelyn and went back again, and went away again, and so \'85
