\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 COLIN:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 
Yeah, six months.  I was still living with Jocelyn.  I was unemployed and living with Jocelyn.  And Peter told me about this job, and Leicester looked commutable.  It\rquote s actually bloody difficult to commute, but it is commutable, and I went for it 
\endash  the Pro
fessor of Epidemiology and Community Medicine, then, as now, is called Michael Clark, and we gave each other a fairly hard time.  He decided he would take me on, and basically, it was to manage all of his non-clinical research, much of which looks like so
cial science research \endash  it\rquote s social gerontology, it\rquote s community health \endash  much of which he\rquote d already got funded. But I had to help manage this stuff, and that\rquote s what the job was \endash 
 Social Scientist - and it was a pure research management job, no teaching or a
nything.  And during that time, when I first started this, I knew who Jan was, because she was very spectacular, she used to have pink hair, she was a pink punk, in the Management Centre, and I knew who she was, but she was always with other people. She l
ed, she actually was a very important person in the Aston Women\rquote 
s Group.  And we bumped into each other one day - and the rest is history!  And after I moved in with Jan, very early, within weeks, we made the decision that the first one of us to get a job a
t - and it was a very short list of towns, it included Oxford, Cambridge, Bristol, Edinburgh, I can\rquote 
t remember where else.  I think that may have been it.  And London, not London.  And that we would apply for jobs in these towns, and the other one would mo
ve.  And Jan got a job as a Lecturer in Business Studies in the Edinburgh Department, and I resigned.  And Michael Clark was very cross with me. I resigned from Leicester, and we moved to Edinburgh in August \rquote 
86.  Between Jan getting the job and moving - someone else who\rquote s name has come up this afternoon \endash  Adrian told me that colleagues, and I\rquote 
ll tell you who they are in a moment, had this big research project, and were about to advertise for a Research Officer.  And so I applied for that job, and got it sh
ortly after arriving.  It is literally true that I was unemployed when I went to Edinburgh.  But I did have a job interview about two weeks later, that was already planned, but it was far from sure I was going to get it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 But you were very senior for that kind of job.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 COLIN:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 Yes.  And I took my second consecutive pay cut, because I was paid }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid8917117 that}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117  at Aston - Social Scientist at Leicester, I went down, from - I can\rquote t even remember what the real sums would be, but in today\rquote s money, I went down from like 
30 grand to 18 grand to 16 grand, something like, literally, went down each time.  And I was very senior, and this is quite important.  And the people who had the money - and I\rquote 
ll tell you what it was for, it was a big data set, Educational Sociology.
