\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 Before we just go on, so you didn\rquote t actually do anything that\rquote s really worth talking about in Leicester? 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 COLIN:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 No. I\rquote ve used it a lot in teaching, and it\rquote s also, I\rquote 
ve had Ph.D. students since, in Social Gerontology.  Most of the projects that I was most closely involved with were in Social Gerontology, and they were all in Melton Mowbray \endash  another small town \endash  because Mike Clark\rquote 
s Department managed all \'85Let\rquote s go back one stage.  Melton Mowbray is a small town, and it\rquote s very unusually got a monopolistic general practice.  There\rquote 
s only one general practice in Melton Mowbray, and it is a teaching practice, and was being used as an exemplar for IT in General Practice, by the Department of Health, and it was all managed from the Leicester Medical School.  
So what?  They managed the Age/Sex Register for this practice, which meant you had a perfect sampling frame for the whole of Melton Mowbray, because everybody, public and private, was on this Age/Sex Register in Melton Mowbray.  Very few towns have a mono
polistic general practice.   We were doing a major study of people living over 70, living alone, who were over 75, and I managed this project.  That got me to know an awful lot about social gerontology, and actually re-reading Peter Townsend - }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid8917117 Old and Alone}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117  and nasty, and all the rest of it.  And I\rquote ve got a couple of papers, with other people, out of that.  One in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\insrsid8917117 Ageing and Society}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 , which is quite good, on measuring morale amongst old people.  The issue is sociologically rich, and very, very close to Peter.
  You can measure isolation, numbers of contacts, networks and all the rest of it, you can do it.  You can do it, but it\rquote s technically difficult.  You can\rquote 
t easily go from that to telling how people feel about it.  You can have people who have lots of contacts who have lost the only significant person \endash  their daughter, their husband, and you can\rquote 
t predict morale, which you can witter on about how you define that, from amount of contact.  Many of the studies only measure contact, but measuring morale is a lot harder, and lack of morale is the killer \endash  not numbers of social contacts, and 
\'93What would you do about that?\'94  That\rquote s what, that\rquote s basically, with data, that\rquote s what the article describes.  And I\rquote ve gone on not being uninterested, and it\rquote s very relevant to Stirling because we\rquote 
re big in old age, and people are stunned that the Principal has an article in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid8917117 Ageing and Society, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 even though it\rquote s an ageing article.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 It\rquote s a big field in Scotland, I guess, too.
