\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 COLIN:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 
Never a wine bar. I helped run a record shop, but never a wine bar.  We were quite big on importing - no, that is literally untrue, whoever said it, it\rquote s false.  But I was very involved in a shop on the Bristol Road, called \'93the Discery\'94
, which is a specialist record shop, and I\rquote m still matey with the people who managed it.  The business was actually, in the end, being killed by what was growing in 1983/4/5, when I was getting into this, by the fact that both Virgin and HMV Meg
astores went on to the High Streets.  Before then, pre-Branson, you couldn\rquote t buy, in most towns, a range of esoterica, in terms of music.  The Megastores, Virgins, even in the esoteric fields that I\rquote m interested in, they\rquote 
ve got everything, therefore they\rquote v
e killed the specialist shops, even the classical music specialist shops have gone.  The jazz and blues shops collapsed all over the country, because Virgin carried a better [range], and they also discounted.  Specialist record shops made their money on n
o
t discounting, and charging above the odds for imports.  Virgin and HMV have never done it.  And just as Waterstones, they may not be a great bookshop, but is deeply threatening to specialist bookshops.  The opening of the second, only the second in the c
ountry, Virgin Megastore, was in Birmingham.  The second in the country is right in the middle of Birmingham.  It was devastating to the specialist record shops.
