\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 So can you tell about the project?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 COLIN:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 Yeah.  There\rquote s something called TVEI, which stands for \'93Technical and Vocational Education Initiative\'94
, which was a very Thatcherite scheme.  It was designed by Lord Young and Geoffrey Hollowell, when he was Permanent Undersecretary at the Department of Education, who went off to become, of course, the Vice-Chancellor at Exeter. I\rquote 
ve chided him with it ever since, because I see him in another part of my life now.  He\rquote s just retired.  And it was the first time anybody other than the Department of Education 
put money into pre-16 schooling.  This was the Department of Employment putting money, directly, into schooling, for Technical and Vocational Education Initiative, in order to make the secondary curriculum more vocational.  And it later got taken over, of
 course, by Manpower Services Commission, in Sheffield \endash  of blessed memory!  You\rquote 
ve got to think what the world was like in the mid-eighties, Thatcher and all the rest of it. The Technical and Vocational Education Initiative is a very, was organisationally fascinating, though that wasn\rquote 
t what I was engaged to do.  But, basically, Local Authorities \endash  Lothians, Strathclyde \endash  could [bid], if they wanted, \'93Consenting adults, you don\rquote t have to do it, but if you do do it, we\rquote ll tell you what you\rquote 
ve got to do.  You have to bid for this money.  It\rquote s new money.  But if you bid for it, you have to do the following things\'94.  The government, hitherto, hadn\rquote 
t worked in that way.  Enterprise in Higher Education was also organised in the same way.  Also, classically, these kind of projects always have evaluation built into them, frequently as a percentage of the overall budget.  So not only, \'93You\rquote 
re going to have to bid for this money, but if you bid for it, you\rquote re going to have to devote ten per cent of it to evaluation.  And, what\rquote s more, we\rquote ll manage the evaluation for you, because we\rquote 
re also going to evaluate it Scotland-wide\'94.  Edinburgh Department of Education bid for, and got, the contract to evaluate TVEI in Scotland.  You can just see how unqualified I am in this world.  I applied for it because Sinfield tells them, \'93
This guy, he\rquote ll do it.  If he says he\rquote ll do it, he\rquote ll do it\'94.  And David Raffe, who\rquote s a famous sociologist in his own right, and a guy called Ken King, who\rquote s an educationalist, really an Africanist, they 
got the money, and Noel Entwistle, who has just retired as Professor of Education, they had the money, and I applied for it and got the job. We had no serious, in your face conversations.  \'93Are you going to do it?  And will you stay?\'94
  And we argued about it, and we agreed I would do it, I would stay, they would reduce the length of the contract from 24 to 22 months, to pay me slightly differently, and I would do it on four days a week, and I wouldn\rquote 
t work Fridays.  And we agreed that that\rquote s what we would do. I did it. I worked with some wonderful people, some of whom are still close friends, who were very junior research persons \endash 
 and this was really great, I shared an office with three young women!  I mean, you get paid to do this!  This was absolutely won
derful!  Some of whom are now quite senior in Educational Sociology.  And this Unit - the Centre for Educational Sociology - which got the money, was headed by Andrew McPherson, famous sociologist in his own right.  Down the street is }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \ul\insrsid8917117 the}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117  Sociology Department \endash 
 Sandy Stewart, John Holmwood, McCrone, and all of this lot. I did the job.  The contract had two halves.  One was to look at change within the classroom, and that was done by what was then Moray House.  We looked at everything outside.  The Scheme pa
id for work experience, employers to come into the schools, teachers to go into employment situations \endash  it\rquote s real David Lodge, nice work country.  It\rquote s that, or it\rquote 
s the screwing of the secondary school curriculum by the DTI.  And, basically, the Scottish 
politicians, who are as clever as hell, took the money and ran, and we had to sort of do - I mean, we did lots of survey work, because the Centre for Educational Sociology had been doing, every other year, a huge survey of Scottish school leavers.  It
\rquote s called \'93The Scottish School Leavers Survey\'94, and they have the best data about into work and school effectiveness, and whether comprehensivisation works and that kind of stuff. They\rquote 
ve got an army of people who did that, and we were on the back of all that. 
 And we had additional questions put into the main survey. But it meant, I [went] straight into Scotland and did fieldwork in Easterhouse, in Glasgow, in Inverclyde, around Greenock, in Dumfries and Galloway, I interviewed loads of kids, and was in the sc
hools.  I couldn\rquote t understand a word some of them said, and Dundee, Dundee\rquote s the hardest town!  And so did loads of this. 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 And you were keeping records of all this work, presumably?
