\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 COLIN:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 Yes.  We wrote up a very very good study, which MSC published.  It\rquote 
s a big fat report, and I invented the title, and there was a row about the title, but in the end, we got away with it.  It was called the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid8917117 Liaisons Dangereuses \endash  Education/Industry Relationships}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 , and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid8917117 Liaisons Dangereuses}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117  sometimes had a question mark and sometimes didn\rquote 
t, but it went away with a question mark, because the compromise was that a question mark could go in the title, not that they were dangerous relationships!  And it\rquote s a good study. The kids knew they were being experimented on, because
, apart from anything else, the whole thing had an experimental model imposed on it, you did it with some classes and not others, and the kids referred to themselves as guinea pigs.  And so this young woman, one of the best of the young women I had to sha
re an office with, called Cathy Howieson, and I wrote a paper which is in a book that David Raffe edited, called }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid8917117 The View from the Hutch}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 
. It was the guinea pigs\rquote  views of what had happened to them. It was a very good paper, I really like it very much, and it\rquote 
s structured against good quantitative data.  We wrote up the experience as a whole, David Raffe and I, in a book edited by a man called Geoffrey Walford, which is based on Bell and Newby, his book is called, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\insrsid8917117 Doing Educational Research}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 , published by Rout
ledge, sells amazingly well to people who do M.Eds., and there is a paper in there by David Raffe and I on what this work was like, and why we did it, and what the significance of it was.  So that\rquote s going on, it\rquote s a big project stuff.  I
\rquote m out and about all the time, Jan\rquote s teaching Business Studies in George Square, and I\rquote m in Buccleugh Place.  And, meanwhile, they\rquote 
ve all fallen out in the Sociology Department down the road.  Sandy used to take me out, [Sandy] Stewart, used to take me out to lunch, and moan about all his colleagues, and I said, \'93Well, it\rquote s nothing to do with me\'94
. Sandy Stewart, who was Professor of Sociology, at that stage, from Cambridge.  And crazily, Edinburgh had given him this job.  Incidentally, when he was appointed, and when they adv
ertised, I was in my dying days at Aston.  They trawled heavily, Edinburgh, and the field that they interviewed for the Chair, was Sandy Stewart, Mick Mann, and Howard.  Margaret Stacey was one of the Externals, and she opposed, resolutely, Howard and Mic
k Mann, on the grounds they weren\rquote t Feminists \endash  well, she was probably right, but it doesn\rquote t seem, to me, a ground for opposing them!  Why they thought Sandy was - Sandy is mad, bad and crazy, and also he\rquote 
s one of those very few, but very dangerous sociologists \endash  Pete Abell\rquote s in the same category \endash  who are convinced they\rquote 
re right, so right, so right are they, that they will distort the curriculum to get correctness in.  So Pete destroyed the Birmingham Department when he was Professor there.  Sandy Stewart n
early destroyed the Edinburgh Department by insisting that the undergraduates }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \ul\insrsid8917117 should}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 
 do this in the first year, and he taught a kind of sociology that I couldn\rquote t understand at all. 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 What kind of sociology is that?
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid9991740 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 COLIN:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 
Well, do you know John Holmwood\rquote s stuff?  Have you read any of this?  It\rquote s got weird forms of sociological theory like, I mean, I can\rquote t even begin to explain it.  It\rquote s Cambridge stratification, it\rquote 
s Prandy and Bob Blackburn.  I mean, what has this ever added?  And, what\rquote s more, it\rquote s
 technically immensely complicated and complex, and you might have to start by teaching first year students elementary calculus so they can understand this work in their second year.  The students vote with their feet in the Scottish system \endash 
 you don\rquote t have to stay in sociology, you can go off.  The Edinburgh Department, as structured up by Tom Burns, was full of people who weren\rquote t sociologists, who were contributing tremendous sociology \endash  Michael Anderson \endash 
 even McCrone\rquote s not really a sociologist in background.  John Orr was out of the Literature Department.  They all, serially, went to the Deans - and Faculties are very important at Edinburgh \endash 
 and asked to leave the Department, and asked just to be moved to another Department, they couldn\rquote t stand this fellow.  And Sandy went and slapped the desk, it was actually over Bechhofer\rquote s job being moved out - it doesn\rquote 
t really matter - but the Department then didn\rquote t get a replacement, because Bechhofer became a kind of free-standing researcher.  And [Sandy] said, \'93I\rquote ll resign if you don\rquote t!\'94  \'93Thank you very much!\'94}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9991740   }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 
When they appointed Sandy, two years earlier, as I said, they did trawl.  My circumstances were clearly known, no one came knocking on my door.  Edinburgh, I thought, was far too grand to take an interest in me, and so I didn\rquote 
t take any interest in Sandy going, because I didn\rquote t think Edinburgh would ever appoint me.  Also, at that time, of all strange people to come after me, Graeme Davis, who was then Vice-Chancellor at Liverpool, wrote to me \endash  presumably
 on advice, in fact, I know it was {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PersonName}}Ray Pahl{\*\xmlclose}\rquote s advice - and wondered whether I might take an interest in the Eleanor Rathbone Chair of Sociology at Liverpool.  I said, \'93I might\'94
.  Jan said she\rquote s not moving to Liverpool, and I said, \'93Well, they haven\rquote t offered me the job yet!\'94
  Well, they did offer me the job, and so I thought I was going to go to Liverpool, and Jan and I were arguing about how we were going to handle it. I said, \'93Edinburgh\rquote s never going to appoint me\'94, and she said, \'93Well, you should apply\'94
.  \'93Well, I can\rquote t apply\'94, you know, \'93I\rquote m going to get the Eleanor Rathbone Chair of Sociology\'94.  I said, \'93They won\rquote t appoint, you know what they\rquote re like\'94
.  And all this is true, and I could actually give you the documentary evidence.  On a handwritten note 
from Sir David Smith, who was then the Principal, who then became Master of Wolfson, a very interesting and very nice man, biologist, a handwritten note, saying I may have noticed they were trying to fill their Chair of Sociology, and the Committee was me
e
ting on such and such a date, and they would conclude their business at lunch on that day, and wondered whether I might care to join the Committee after lunch, and if I would, just as a courtesy, could he see an up-to-date CV?  And so, very powerful Commi
ttee, not just because it was Lockwood and Richard Brown, but internally, you know, they later became my colleagues.  And the competition included Gordon Marshall, by the way, at that time, so, you know, Gordon was thinking, \'93Mmm, I\rquote 
ve got the job!\'94  But I\rquote d, meanwhile, accepted the Eleanor Rathbone Chair.  David Smith, who\rquote s a wonderful man, said did I want the weekend to think about it?  It was a Friday, I remember.  I said, \'93Well, not really\'94.  He said, \'93
Well, you come in and tell me on Monday morning you still want our job, and I\rquote ll talk to Graeme Davis for you\'94
.  And I did, and he did.  The interesting thing was, I was always very irritated by the salary level that Graeme Davis had offered me.  I knew enough about which way was up to know that he should 
have offered me a bit more, but he insisted that was it, and that was what he was going to hold me to.  Edinburgh being Edinburgh, and I later ran the system, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \ul\insrsid8917117 never}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8917117  talked about money at all.  The salary offer was just slightly above what I thought they should have offered me!  And I thought, \'93What a wonderful place!\'94  So that\rquote s \rquote 88.  Got the job in March \rquote 
88, and in as Head of Department.  They were very pleased to get me, and the troops clearly wanted me to be appointed. And probably I then had, professio
nally, the best ten years of my life.  I was ten years as Head of Department and Vice-Principal.  Edinburgh had a roughish time in the late eighties/early nineties, I mean in ways that don\rquote 
t really matter, but I was just the Head of Department, in a University with 120-odd Departments and a Medical School and a Law School, and being Head of Sociology is no big deal.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid8917117 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 And, Colin, were you going on researching at that point?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 COLIN:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 I was finishing, yes - no, we went on.  Momentum, ah!  The Centre for Educational Sociology is now in my Department, I\rquote 
m the boss!  So I moved from being a hired hand research to - and everybody found this all very funny and entertaining. I also had the Science Studies Unit and various other things \endash  David Edge and Donald McKenzie and David Bloor \endash 
 all these bits, a big and successful Department.  Momentum with all this educational stuff, there was continual momentum, and some of the stuff that I\rquote ve told you was a part of the project, the project lasted 22 months, though we go
t the report in within those 22 months, lots of the near academic and academic stuff was what I did in my first year, whilst being Head of Department.  And, in fact, it then became, what the hell else was I going to do?  Well, I went on writing and publis
hing, because my mid-career training \endash  I haven\rquote t really gone on about this \endash  I learnt how to handle big data sets whilst I was in the Centre for Educational Sociology, and they had - every two years they\rquote 
d interviewed about 12,000 kids, and so from 1972 thr
ough the whole of this period, there was this vast longitudinal data set, and all on the main frame, and I learnt how to handle a lot of that.  And I did stuff on region, religion, lots of stuff on Catholic education \endash 
 much of this is published in various places \endash  and went on doing that probably for about two and a half years, and then I was beginning to think, you know, \'93What the hell else should I really do?\'94
  Then I fell in with the criminologists, quite good criminologists at Edinburgh, in the Law Schoo
l, they would be in a Sociology Department anywhere else, and started to do stuff on crime in Scotland, which was actually related, more than anything else, to what in Scotland are called \'93Schemes\'94, housing estates \endash 
 public housing and the collapse of - it\rquote s the Easterhouse, Craigmillar, Castle Milk, those kind of places.  Because I was also interested in housing - the Oz interest, I did a lot of work on housing \endash 
 and wrote the first draft of the Housing Chapter in Peter\rquote s big book on Poverty.  I bet you didn\rquote t know that.  It actually says, he actually thanks me for my work on housing.  I\rquote 
ve had a long time interest in housing.  And so I went on thinking about those things. But then what?  No, let\rquote s get them in the right order. Because there is a consistency.  I went on doing a lot of teaching \endash 
 I had quite a lot of postgraduates by then as well.  And there was a smallish but significant kind of staff and teaching development Unit at Edinburgh, called TLA \endash  Teaching, Learning and Assessment.  It was funded by
 the University, and it would do staff development for you about teaching, it ran the induction programme for staff \endash  this was long before it\rquote s all certificated \endash 
 and did a bit of research on what was effective teaching in higher education.  But it had to be managed, and there was a small \endash  Edinburgh being Edinburgh \endash 
 there was a Committee, and the guy who had been Chair of the Committee was retiring.  I knew these people because I\rquote d done some development work with TLA, I used to go to meetings and give seminars and so on. They just said, \'93
This guy, Bradley, is going.  Can\rquote t you chair our Committee?\'94  So that\rquote s agreed by Senate and all the rest of it, This is no big deal.  But the people there were very important to me because they spotted, early, and this i
s, the next big career opportunity: the importance of audit and quality assurance.  And Edinburgh was about as ready for it as you were! Utterly unprepared for the rigours of what was coming over the horizon.  And I convinced David Smith, who was still Pr
incipal, that this was going to be serious.  There was no way of avoiding it.  There was going to be something called \'93Academic Audit\'94, and there was no way of handling it.  There wasn\rquote 
t a university, there were twelve faculties, some of which were tiny, most of which didn\rquote t speak to each other.  Different rules of assessment, different scales.  And I said, \'93You just won\rquote t survive\'94
.  And he, while I was still Head of Department, he appointed me, somewhat to my surprise, as his advisor on quality assurance \endash  this is the career move \endash  and I got paid three grand a year or something, for being his advisor on this.  I wasn
\rquote t a member of the Senior Management Team or whatever.  He went, because of a financial crisis.  He was about two years off retirement.  The pla
ce was evilly and poorly run.  During this period, sacked Director of Finance.  Edinburgh had borrowed its way through the eighties, it hadn\rquote t expanded when it ought to have done, and we didn\rquote t know where the money was \'85 it wasn\rquote 
t of the modern world.  Que
ntin Thompson, who is, perhaps, the most distinguished educational management consultant, then working for Coopers Lybrand, he - we were Quentin Thompsoned. The whole place was restructured in a management report.  And basically, one of the unpublished su
ggestions was they\rquote 
d got to get rid of virtually all the people in senior academic positions, all of whom had got there by buggins turn.  There were some dreadful people.  There was a Pro-Vice-Chancellor, who was Dennis Harding, Professor of Archaeology, wh
o eventually virtually went to jail for sort of fraudulent use of his money, and things like this.  But they were all of the Old School.  You cannot begin to parody what a Dean of Arts, or Dean of Divinity looks like at Edinburgh.  They did not manage the
ir money, they didn\rquote t know their numbers, or little quality assurance, or something called \'93The Research Assessment Exercise\'94.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 And what were they doing, then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 COLIN:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 Oh, chairing professional colleagues.  But there was no central management either, and you\rquote 
re talking about a really big university.  Quentin Thompson and Coopers Lybrand put in this massive report.  They were already, virtually Edinburgh was in Special Measures by the old UGC, on a kind of monthly report \endash  I\rquote 
m getting this right.  And three new Vice-Principals were appointed, none of whom had been Deans \endash  the first time in Edinburgh\rquote s history that they\rquote 
d ever done this.  One, a man called Andrew Miller, who was my predecessor at Stirling;  me;  and Michael Anderson.  And in we came, and 
I looked after the whole of the teaching policy of the University.  Mike was doing the budgeting.  And Andrew Miller was doing research.  And up to that time, Edinburgh said it wasn\rquote 
t possible to have a research policy, research was what scholars and gentlemen did, how can you have a research policy?  And we dragged it, kicking and screaming, into the modern world.  And it was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \ul\insrsid8917117 the}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117  most amazing opportunity for me, because I did the first audit visit, managed it, did the whole of the documentation.  I had to 
do all the training associated with it.  I also managed something like 27 consecutive subject reviews and teaching quality assessments, and put in the system that did it.  David Smith, bless his cotton socks, goes.  There was a long interregnum, Mike Ande
rson was Acting Principal, before Stuart Sutherland comes.  And Stuart, who\rquote s just retired, a really powerful guy to work with, made it absolutely clear that he was keeping the team intact, even though it meant he didn\rquote 
t have to do anything - there was a streak of laziness in Stuart.  I was then made Senior Vice-Principal, and so I was, in effect, Sutherland\rquote s deputy, and I did everything he wouldn\rquote t do, couldn\rquote t do, or shouldn\rquote 
t do, for something like nearly five years.  I mean, nobody knew where the skeletons were, I\rquote 
d usually shoved them in the cupboards, and had them killed in the first place!  (LAUGHS)  And the big thing I did, other than quality assurance, was that I managed the merger with Moray House, and brought in, that was \'a325m. a year turnover, an
d 150 colleagues and so on, and endless troubles about car parking!  And that was brilliant.  And in all honesty, thereafter, what was I doing in terms of research?  Not real research.  I was continuing to teach, three times a week, first year sociology, 
and by the end we were teaching a Sociology of Modern Industrial Society, only on Scottish material \endash 
 we taught it all on Scottish material.  It was pretty good.  Then I also managed an army of the tinies who did the classes, because I had all these graduate students, and that\rquote 
s nice, because you give a lot of patronage, not just giving them work, but you get them jobs and all the rest of it, and some of them are now middle level of particularly Scottish sociology, many of whom were in the Edinburgh Department at that time.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 You did say, I don\rquote t know whether you can repeat this, that you really enjoy teaching, and I\rquote 
m wondering what you really enjoy about it?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 COLIN:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 I think I like the social contact. , I\rquote ve learnt that I actually like the dissemination
 of ideas, as well as the creation of them.  I\rquote ve often had some of my better research ideas in teaching situations.  Scientists always find that very puzzling when you say that to them, because they say, they\rquote 
re usually researching way beyond where they\rquote re teaching.  I like seeing people develop.  I\rquote ve often tried to organise teaching structures where I have the same class over a period of years.  I did that in Oz, where I\rquote 
d take a cohort through for three years and so on.  And I\rquote ve done a bit of that, well, I would try and get my people to do my Honours classes \endash  in Edinburgh it\rquote 
s harder to take them all the way through.  I also like generic teaching, and I\rquote ll explain what I mean.  Early on, I discovered \endash  not that I think I write particularly well \endash  but I can teach writing.  Partly influenced by Becker
\rquote s book, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid8917117 Writing for Social Scientists}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 , I developed a way of handling that, and I ran, for about six years at Edinburgh, \'93
Writing for Post Graduate Students\'94.  Though it was actually also at the wrong end, yo
u always got beginning students doing it, where you thought you ought to actually have people who were finishing, doing it.  But it meant I could teach right across the social sciences, and I\rquote 
d get about 20 people a year to come to these Writing Workshops.  You could only get in if you bought }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid8917117 Writing}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 
.  I partly taught that with an anthropologist called Jonathan Spencer, and we used to do that together. I was just very enthusiastic about it, and I thought a lot about the big lectures, and how you handle it. 
 I quite like the major pedagogic opportunity, as it were.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 You like a big crowd?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 COLIN:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 I don\rquote 
t mind a big audience.  And I, on the other hand, will relate to small group stuff as well.  The Edinburgh situation was demanding, and you had to write it.  Real competition, there were tremendously good first year performers at Edinburgh, particula
rly in some of the Humanities Departments.  But Edinburgh students, who can vote with their feet, don\rquote t forget, the largest single source of students at Edinburgh is Eton, so you\rquote ve got to think who\rquote 
s likely to be there, and all these blokes with their baseball hats back to front, with their feet up, from very expensive education south of the Border, and if they didn\rquote t like what you were doing, they\rquote d shout, \'93Fast forward\'94
, and so, you really had to do - and I quite liked that.  I also think I had, and still have, a very strong line on sociology being important and significant, and it\rquote s a good education and it gives you a way of thinking about things. You\rquote 
re a better person for taking this all on, you don\rquote t have to be a convert to it, but it\rquote s actually chall
enging and all the rest of it.  So I try and convey that degree of enthusiasm.  And I try to keep my teaching scholarly, in the sense that I\rquote 
ve developed a way, at Edinburgh, of keeping some of the performances with the same structure, but often changing t
he content - I often think of a new series of examples, or a new book had come out, something like that - and I tried, desperately, to keep up-to-date.  Because you\rquote ve got to remember how young a lot of those people were.  You can\rquote 
t even talk about Thatcher by the end, that\rquote s a bit kind of like talking about Clement Attlee!  It\rquote s a slightly obscure and ill-defined concept, it\rquote s not quite there.  And I\rquote 
ve gone on with an utter commitment to mainstream sociology.  So nothing about body piercing in my courses, might be a bit about subcultures and youth culture, but, I mean, we don\rquote t teach \'93the body\'94 or whatever, \'93class crisis and the state
\'94.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 What about sexuality?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 COLIN:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 A bit.  A bit.  Not all that much.  I didn\rquote t have to, in the Edinburgh Department, b
ecause there was loads of it about.  There were lots of other people offering.  I was doing the first - remember the Edinburgh structure, there\rquote s two first years \endash  I mean, there\rquote 
s a first year and a second year, then they become Honour students in the third year, and have two years in Honours.  So there\rquote 
s a huge second year problem as well, what do you do in the second year?  Well, the course was called something like Gender, Sexuality and Social change, was what you went on to after getting this serious stuff about Weber and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid8917117 The Protestant Ethic}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 .  They went on to all of that.  I did quite a lot about mainstream stuff about women\rquote 
s employment and household structure, but not all that much, in all honesty, about sexuality and gender orientation, and I didn\rquote t do all that much about that.  But I had colleagues, it was their life\rquote 
s work, like Lynn Jamieson, this is what they did, so why should I do it?  So I didn\rquote t do that. It\rquote s a good question to ask, because sociology, during the period I was teaching it, was f
eminising, and by the time I left, and even more now, Honours students are disproportionately female.  First year is still a kind of 60 per cent female, 40 per cent male, but as you go up the system, and the graduate students/Ph. Ds. even out a bit.  But 
Honours students got to the stage where blokes were rare \endash 
 and they were gay, and so on!  So it was quite interesting.  Why that was is quite hard to explain, and you know, we used to ask questions about it, but it was quite difficult. I was very enthused w
ith all that.  And it was a natural, for me, to take quality assurance seriously, because I knew what I was doing it for, which was to try and improve, systematically, the quality of particularly the undergraduate experience.  And Edinburgh colleagues wer
e not student-focused.  Some were, but by and large, they weren\rquote t.  And tried to get things like decent reading lists and office hours, and \'85
 you know, of the modern world, and, therefore, I rode that.  But also it was a vehicle for me being politically act
ive in higher education, firstly in Scotland, then in Britain, in that I was appalled by the way the sector in Scotland fell over and played dead in front of the Scottish Higher Education Funding Council, on quality assurance.  And I can remember talking 
to David Smith and saying, \'93Why don\rquote t we organise?\'94  He said, \'93Well, we can\rquote t organise the Universities\'94.  So I created something called \'93The Quality Assurance Forum\'94
, which had my equivalent from every university in Scotland, and their senior administrativ
e support, meeting.  By the end, we were telling the Funding Council how to write their documentation, and we mobilised against the Funding Council.  I would actually say that that was one of my more significant achievements in Scotland.  It meant I was i
ncredibly well-known, apart from anything else.  It\rquote s why I\rquote m doing what I\rquote 
m currently.  When they want someone to do quality assurance at the E-University, and pay me for coming down here, who do they send for?  Not because I knew about it, but also I recognised what you could do with it. It\rquote s become }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \ul\insrsid8917117 the}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 
 mechanism by which degree awarding powers are now created. Poor old Bolton, for example, is currently being quality assured to death, because until they get through it, they won\rquote t be given degree awarding p
owers.  Nobody anticipated quality assurance doing those kind of things.  Won\rquote 
t be able to sell the courses for the E-university without a degree of quality assurance.  And the universities have got to trust the E-university to set up something which doesn\rquote 
t give them a hard time, because otherwise we get delay, and colleagues get irritated, and they also say, \'93Look, trust us, we\rquote re Leeds\'94.  And I say, \'93Yes, but give me the evidence that I can trust you\'94.  I\rquote 
ve understood how to do that, for quite a long time.  It meant that I was a natural to chair the English Funding Council\rquote s Quality Assurance Committee, which I did when I was in England.  Then when I went back across the Border, I said, \'93It
\rquote s illogical for me to chair the English Committee, because the English system is different to Scotland\'94.  And so I, against all expectations - well, the kind of things that happen is, people come up to you and say, \'93
When I see you, I think of quality\'94.  But they don\rquote t quite mean that!  They actually mean the dreaded qu
ality assurance stuff!  And if there are two things that normal conventional university managers, or heads of institutions really, will tell you are difficult \endash  both of which I\rquote ve done a lot of, and really enjoyed \endash 
 one is quality assurance, and the other is mergers. I chaired the Scottish Funding Council\rquote s Mergers Committee, and put three free-standing teacher education colleges into universities.  I\rquote 
ve also done a wonderful de-merger, where I took something out of another institution and put it somewhere 
else.  And I like that work.  And, if anything, I think I ought to get paid for doing this for some kind of consultancy firm.  Most of this, you do for free.  I got the opportunity to do that because of being at Edinburgh, being in the right place at the 
right time when quality assurance came over the horizon, and then given the space to do it.  Because David Smith didn\rquote t know what to do with all this stuff, and, as I said, Stuart Sutherland, though he\rquote s an influential guy, didn\rquote 
t want to be bothered with any of this.  And if Edinburgh\rquote s got anything like a modern structure now, me and two or three other people did a load of that.  Now they\rquote 
ve just been re-Coopered and Lybrand, and the structures have been changed again, in ways that I understand, but I don\rquote t have anything to do with.  So why did I leave?  I think I recognised, well, firstly, the ground rules are, you can\rquote 
t do it forever \endash  being a PVC or Deputy Principal \endash in the end of the sector I was then working.  Edinburgh, you couldn\rquote t do it forever.  An
d my predecessors and my peers, they died in office, they became Vice-Chancellors or Principals elsewhere, or they retired.  Nobody ever went back.  And the few that did were pathetic.  Or their lives became pathetic.  There was no way back.  Particularly
, often, they\rquote d gone back to Departments that were thrusting ahead, and there was no way that you could go back.  And so I knew I wasn\rquote t aiming to die, and I was too young to retire, and I knew I\rquote 
d got to get out. Sutherland was quite open about it, and we talked about where I should go, and what getting Head of Institution\rquote 
s job is, as unpredictable as getting a Chair, I think.  Perhaps more so - judging by some of the crazies who get these jobs, it must be very unpredictable indeed!  I tried, seriously, re
ally hard, and I think probably came second, to become Principal of Aberdeen.  Jan didn\rquote t particularly want to go to Aberdeen, and the guy who got it is fine.  He\rquote 
s not one of the crazies, and I can see why they did it, and I could also see why they shouldn\rquote t have given it to me.  And having got really close, and it\rquote 
s a long complex and punishing process, and having got really close, I then had itchy feet. Having got that close, I was on the road.  And it\rquote s all Gavin McKenzie\rquote s fault.  He\rquote s now dead, but Ga
vin, the head-hunter extraordinaire, sociologist, my generation, in the first ever BSA Summer School, where I first met Mick Mann, Gavin McKenzie was also there.  Gavin invented modern academic head-hunting for Saxton Bamfeld.  Gavin rang me one day and s
aid, \'93You\rquote re going to say no, but just listen to me.  I\rquote ll tell you why Bradford\rquote s interesting\'94.  And he came after me to get - Gavin\rquote 
s job is to get you on a short-list, for the people who are paying, to get a short-list that looks good, and he was trying 
to get me on his short-list.  And because Rachel, my oldest, was then living in Leeds, we stayed with Rachel and I just drove over to Bradford, on my own, without any of the others, to have a poke around.  I\rquote 
d like to sort of see it.  And I was kind of missing Race and Ethnic Relations and all that, which was the only good bit about being in Aston. That\rquote 
s the other thing I was doing at Edinburgh, I was teaching Race and Ethnic Relations, me and Patricia Jeffreys, we were the only people teaching anything on
 race and ethnicity in the Social Science Faculty, which probably means in the University, and I quite like that stuff.  And I could see why it was interesting, it was kind of seductive.  Again the rest is history.  I was appointed.  And it was good, and 
I learnt how to do it, I suppose.  I\rquote ve restructured Bradford.  But we, basically, very early on \'85
