none of this really matters, but she had a trajectory through Edinburgh and was now in the Sociology Department, having been formally moved, having got out of Business Studies, and she\rquote s now a Reader in the Sociology Department, and it\rquote 
s all right.  It\rquote s okay.  It\rquote s got worse since, because virtually everyone\rquote s bought themselves out, and so I think they\rquote re more pissed off with it.  But she wasn\rquote 
t easily going to give it up.  A bit like a kind of re-run, life re-runs itself the second time as a farce, I suppose!  A bit like going to Australia.  I wasn\rquote 
t quite clear how long I was going to stay.  Did we really want to move lock, stock and barrel?  And Jan and the kids were very - unlike Jocelyn, I suppose - very committed to being in Scotland, and liking Scotl
and very much.  And I thought that what I was doing, given that they thought that they were very smart with themselves \endash  a lot of universities do, by giving me a five-year contract \endash 
 I made it clear that five years meant five years at most.  Indeed, this would have been my last year, and I was going to stop.  What I was going to do thereafter, I didn\rquote 
