\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 COLIN:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 Yeah.  Yeah, particularly the politics of it.  I mean, big and small \'93P\'94
.  We had tremendous programmes on, you know, Saturday morning universities.  The CVCP, as it was, Universities UK, has written up a whole series of case-studies, two of which I was associated with, called, \'93From Elitism to Inclusion\'94.
 One of them is the Edinburgh Programme, called \'93LEAPS\'94 \endash  Lothian Equal Access Programme for Schools \endash 
 which I used to run, which was a multi-exit schools-based.  Multi-exit meant any institution, it was run, led by Edinburgh, but you could go anywhere out
 of it.  And it had a Summer School, and it was for 18-year olds.  But also, Bradford had a very interesting community based access programme, and it was community based because the schooling system, which was pretty bad, and had one of the worst OFSTED R
eports of all time, and run by some Neanderthal Trade Unionists, would not let the University into the schools, on the grounds that it was none of their business.  And so the University had set up working with community groups, so\endash called \endash 
 Pakistani youth groups, Bangladeshi football teams, hockey clubs \endash  had set up this amazing community-based programme, which is written up, there\rquote 
s a good, big case study. It was very effective about getting young Asian people - and ethnicity in Bradford means Asian, there\rquote s hardly any Afro-Caribbeans, they\rquote ve all migrated to Leeds, and they moved out, and it\rquote 
s become an Asian city.  I was very involved with all that, and very involved with conventional politics.  I wasn\rquote t back in the Labour Party but I went out and about wi
th a lot of activists.  I also discovered something called Common Purpose, which actually exists in Edinburgh as well, but I didn\rquote t know that when I was in Edinburgh, which is formally, it\rquote 
s a not-for-profit community organisation that does a lot of stuff \endash  development \endash 
 and I chaired Common Purpose.  It was for middle level and rising people in the City, to know each other and to be engaged with community development and so on.  I\rquote m also just starting it in Central Scotland as well.  It\rquote s run by, well, the
 term was almost invented for her, a woman called Julia Middleton, so she\rquote s a social entrepreneur \endash  in Charles Handy\rquote s terms of the words \endash  and she\rquote 
s created this organisation.  You get loads of charity money to do it.  And that gave me an apolitical way, 
or non-Party political way, of being active in Bradford.  And one of the things I did was have to do a lot of succession planning when I was on the way out to keep it going, and it\rquote s still going. 
