\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 COLIN:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 Yeah.  Yeah.  Okay.  Okay.  And to go with him, and to meet, for him to introduce me to the informants that I\rquote 
d read about, that was quite \'85 And I went, for example, to see William Whyte of}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid8917117  Street Corner Society}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 
, deliberately.  I went on a pilgrimage to Ithaca, in Cornell, to actually meet him, to talk about }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid8917117 Street Corner Society}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 .  I like to see the people.  I\rquote 
d like him to take me round Boston, but, of course, those days are long gone.  But then, Bradford was doing business in India, it had partners in India, something called the ILLM \endash  the Integrated Learning and Management. 
 It was a private business school in Delhi, and we started to validate their degrees.  There are no private universities in India - Socialism still exists - and so all the private bodies give overseas degrees, and Bradford got into this business, quite lu
cratively, quite early, and quite respectably, it works quite good.  That meant I was going out to do graduations.  And so I was going about twice a year \endash 
 once to mind the business, and once to do graduations.  Some of the people they are working with are rich and powerful and significant.  The Rai family that owns this place, is probably about the sixth or seventh wealthiest, of new money.  You can
\rquote t talk about old money in India.  But they own things like telecommunications concessions, steel mills, hotel
s, tourist resorts.  So this is significant people to me.  And when I tell, like the Indian High Commissioner, as I did the other day, who I was with, \'93Oh!\'94
, I mean this is knowing significant people.  They just open loads of doors. Had I stayed at Bradford, I might well have tried to get some work on changes on the Indian economy.  I was quite interested in doing some work there.  But I\rquote 
ve now been to India \endash  I haven\rquote t been since I\rquote ve been at Stirling \endash  but I was going, I\rquote ve been to India about a dozen tim
es in five years, and was watching the way Delhi was changing and things like that.  And pilgrimages, again, I went to see Andre Beteille, and I\rquote d met Andre on the Essex Campus with David Lockwood, and Andre is thanked for reading the }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid8917117 Community Studies}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117  man
uscript.  I went to see Andre and Andre introduced me to his children, who seemed to be about as old as I am, and so on!  And Andre also I saw in Edinburgh, he had a Fellowship in Edinburgh, and he came and taught Durkheim to my students.  So he introduce
d me to his people, and I was taking a real interest.  ILLM wanted to move some of their work from Bradford to Stirling which you can\rquote t possibly do, and relations are not so good now, because I wouldn\rquote 
t do it.  They wanted to move some of their validation on computing to us, just to stay with me.  And I had to - I\rquote ll tell you a funny story about them in a moment.  But they just couldn\rquote t accept that I couldn\rquote 
t take it with me, it just wasn\rquote t acceptable.  Now, this looks like Indian modernity, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \ul\insrsid8917117 real}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117  modernity, these are of the modern world, and they\rquote 
ve got software houses and all the rest of it.  Luke, my next to eldest, who\rquote s a kind of sycrentist Buddhist, he went out, partly because his organisation was very interested in celebrating some Ghandian anniversary \endash  I can\rquote 
t remember whether it was a birth or death \endash  and the Indians were terribly impressed that he and his friends were out there to think about all this sort of stuff.  And Luke\rquote s heavily into humming, and they went, \'93
Oh, what a spiritual young man\'94.  And the Rai family, when he was out there, put a car at his disposal, and various other things, and Luke couldn\rquote t believe all this!  So, it is of the modern world.  Until old man Rai, who\rquote 
s a multi, multi, multi millionaire, asked Luke, my son, whether he would inherit my university!  (LAUGHS)  He suddenly realised, he suddenly realised, we hadn\rquote 
t quite got there!  There was still a bit of a gap!  The leap to modernity had not been made!  (LAUGHS)  I just loved it!  Let\rquote s just complete, then we can stop.  St
irling.  I was not looking to move from Bradford, with the minor exception, and I didn\rquote t look for it, the head-hunting thing is very invidious, because there\rquote 
s loads of talk behind the chair, as it were, all the time, about these jobs.  And again, the head
-hunters came after me about Newcastle, and I would admit to taking an interest in Newcastle because it was in the right direction.  The guy who got it, I know rather well, he used to be Dean of Medicine at Edinburgh, and he and I are fairly friendly.  An
d I was interviewed for it and didn\rquote t get it.  It wasn\rquote 
t that I then had itchy feet, I then really thought I was going to do the five years bit, But Andrew Miller, who was my predecessor, and he and I were colleagues at Edinburgh, he just came up to me at a
 Universities UK Meeting in Durham, actually, it was on Stockton Campus at the University of Durham, and told me that I really really had got to go after Stirling.  I told him why I wouldn\rquote t \endash 
 50 per cent of which was Bradford, and 50 per cent was the fact that they had a terribly terribly terribly good woman called Vicky Bruce, who I know very well, I\rquote 
ve been on the Scottish Funding Council with her, who I thought should have the job.  He just told me, outright, that she wasn\rquote t going to apply, she had said she wasn\rquote t going to apply.  So I said, \'93Are you absolutely convinced she\rquote 
s not going to apply, and guarantee she doesn\rquote t apply, you can consider me to be a candidate, but I\rquote m not going to apply against her\'94.  Because the risky business in the trade, of course, is if you go after these things and it\rquote 
s known that you don\rquote t get it, if it ever leaks, you\rquote re dead in Bradford, so all sorts of problems.  And I thought Vicky was going to get this job, and she didn\rquote t apply for it, and I got it.  And she now is head
 of one of the Colleges in Edinburgh, Edinburgh has restructured into three Colleges, these so-called \'93Mini-Vice-Chancellors\'94 and she\rquote s now that.  She\rquote 
s only just a close friend.  And, indeed, just to complete these stories, when Adrian comes to supper next Saturday, Vicky\rquote s coming as well!  Her husband is Head of Psychology at Glasgow. Stirling was, is great, and I\rquote 
ve done something very unusual.  It\rquote s unusual, one, because people don\rquote t move between institutions at this level, and secondly, if they do, they move up.  And I\rquote ve moved to somewhere which has a budget almost the same as Bradford
\rquote s.  It has a very different position and brand image, and a different location in the trade, and a different portfolio of subjects, but very rarely do people move between institutions.  They move from one that\rquote s there to one that\rquote 
s up there, but there\rquote s very little movement, and almost the system is designed to stop it, because you get appointed too close to the end of your career to make movement possible nowadays, for g
ood or ill.  And so whether it was intentional or not, there is actually very little movement between institutions, so it\rquote s very unusual to do it.  It means that I have inbuilt comparisons all the time, because I\rquote 
ve worked in so many different institutions. It is extraordinarily good being back in Scotland.  I mean, I like it.  And it\rquote s not to do with the climate or the scenery, I mean, it\rquote 
s to do with, you know, being a small system where you know everybody \endash  I was very well known before \endash  and it\rquote s odd, I\rquote 
m a boy from Tunbridge Wells, and I cut my teeth in Essex, but I feel myself to be a kind of Scottish actor, acting on the Scottish scene, and I do know them all, and I like Stirling in particular.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 Does it matter, not being English?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 COLIN:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 
Not discernibly to me.  It might be interesting to ask other people, but not discernibly to me.  Most people, if they knew I was at Bradford, have suppressed it, and sort of think I was at Edinburgh forever and a day.  And also, it\rquote 
s very weird, to have a Scottish name!  And there are other famous Colin Bells who are Scottish, and people, if they think about it at all, until I open my mouth, don\rquote t know - and I mean, I can\rquote t even imitate a Scottish accent!  It\rquote 
s quite weird!  I can pass, I can just about pass for Strine in Australia, but I can\rquote t - I can turn on a full-blown Australian accent, I can even do different versions of an Australian accent, I can\rquote t do Scottish, and I don\rquote 
t know why this is!  My children have Scottish accents.  And I can\rquote t do it.  It\rquote s quite odd.   But Stuart Sutherland who, curiously, whose first teaching job was at Stirling, said, and he\rquote s right, \'93It\rquote ll fit you like a glove
\'94.   And it does.   And domestically, it\rquote s as easy as hell, because, the houses are only 45 minutes apart, and there\rquote 
s also a house on the Stirling Campus, which is - a pretty fantastic place to be,  and the house in Edinburgh is only 45 minutes away, so that\rquote s solved all that, domestically.  And the University is on a roll.  Bradford is, it\rquote 
s not quite in as deep a hole as one expected it to be, but it\rquote s a pretty deep hole, and a very challenging portfolio of disciplines: who the hell\rquote 
s going to read French at Bradford? Not many people, believe you me!  Not many want to do it at Stirling, but a few more.  But they\rquote v
e also got the horror story that is engineering, which is space and staff and technicians and glass-blowers, and a lot of boring old farts who can\rquote t believe that the world has changed and that the students don\rquote t want to do it any more.  That
\rquote s Bradford, yeah.  That\rquote s Bradford, yeah, yeah. 
