\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 Can I ask you, in general, about managing, being a Vice-Chancellor?  Do you think it\rquote 
s an advantage, being a sociologist, or not?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 COLIN:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 I don\rquote t think it\rquote s a disadvantage, though, of course, you and I know the ran
ge of people who are sociologists are almost as wide as the range of human beings.  So what is it?  Some of them, they\rquote 
re as difficult and as anally retentive as an engineer!  I think I have tremendous inbuilt advantage with being a sociologist, about context of higher education, social structure, class, mobility.  I tend to say things like, \'93
As Goldthorpe has shown, we\rquote re here to reproduce the service class\'94, and it\rquote s partly a joke, but partly that kind of thing.  If anything, people like me are slightly hostile to management literature, the management gurus, you know, we don
\rquote t read that stuff to learn, and maybe other people do.  I have had an interest in, over the years, in the Sociology of Organisations, but not in any detailed way, and as soon as it goe
s off into management and organisation as taught in Business Schools, I turn off, I\rquote m not terribly interested.  I think I\rquote ve got a personal advantage which doesn\rquote t come from sociology at all, and it\rquote 
s not a very usual characteristic of a sociologist, in that I\rquote m very much of an intellectual gadfly \endash  I\rquote 
m interested in wide ranges of things, and I really like being on Appointment Committees because you learn about all sorts of weird and wonderful things that people are up to.  And I have got half a degree in history \endash 
 terribly useful!  Half a degree in geography \endash  terribly useful!  I did quite a lot of politics at Keele.  I did geology at Keele.  I\rquote d moved into sociology and did quite a lot of social anthropology.  I\rquote 
ve had a serious interest in criminology and social gerontology, and I like doing that, you know, I mean I like that range of things.  I interview once a semester, in Stirling - and there are two in a year \endash 
 I see every Head of Department once a semester, I might see them dozens of times for other reasons, but they have to come in and we talk about what they\rquote re doing and all the rest of it.  And I find there\rquote s hardly a Department that I\rquote 
m not really interested in what they\rquote re doing.  I like to know what they\rquote re doing. I\rquote ve worked in universities \endash  I mean, Sloman didn\rquote t show the slightest interest in us, as far as I can see, and other people I\rquote 
ve worked with don\rquote t show the slightest interest, but I try to show an interest.  I also like being out and about.  I have most of these meetings in their office, I normally go to the Head of Institution\rquote 
s Office, I go to them, mainly because it\rquote s a campus university and you walk across very easily, but it\rquote s nice to be out and about and see, and see them.  I don\rquote t think that\rquote s being a sociologist, except the thin
g which, you know, I hadn\rquote t really thought about systematically, until you said, \'93Oh, you like going to see things\'94, and I still like going to see things.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 Watching people work.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 COLIN:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 Yes.  Watching people.  I go into their offices, I like to know how they \'85 Part of it is saying \'93Hi\'94
 to the secretaries, I do it to be seen, and until very recently - it\rquote s slightly wearing off - I was familiarising myself with the place.  Its budget is 50 per cent bigger than Essex\rquote s is currently.  It\rquote s bigger than Essex.  And it
\rquote s not quite as compact, it\rquote s in bits and pieces, so you have to go to different places.  But I need to be in their offices and to see them.  And it\rquote s got some of Essex\rquote s characteristics too, that there\rquote 
s people who have been there forever.  There are the Joan Busfield figures who really, you know, you can\rquote t tell anything to!  You suggest something, and they say, \'93Oh, we did that in 1978\'94, you know!  (LAUGHS)  Or whatever.  And then there
\rquote s loads of movers.  I tease them about stayers and movers and that sort of thing.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 That\rquote s another interest of yours, is it?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 COLIN:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 Yeah.  Yes, again.  Again.  As a sociologist, I\rquote 
ve probably told you that those of us who are Heads of Institutions, who are sociologists, meet, and we ask ourselves the question that you\rquote ve asked me.  And the consensus is that it doesn\rquote t make a lot of difference, we find it difficult 
\'85
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 So, other than being more \'85
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 COLIN:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 More societally aware.  And, you see, not many of us \'85 we\rquote ve talked about this, feel drawn to comment
 on public affairs.  You see, Giddens does, and we tease Tony about instant comment and so on, but other people, Janet Finch or Bob Burgess, aren\rquote t drawn into making instant comment, and so the consensus is that probably not.  There\rquote 
s an alternative sort of explanation, why so many at this time?  And Stephen Hill, who\rquote s at LSE and Giddens\rquote s deputy \endash  good sociologist, has just been appointed Head of Royal Holloway \endash  we thought there wasn\rquote 
t going to be another one.  So there\rquote s another sociologist who has climbed the slippery pole.  We got slightly unsatisfactory explanations about the best and the brightest being drawn into sociology in the late sixties, and th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16202747 at wouldn\rquote t happen any}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 more.  Where do the best and the brightest go [now]?  Well, I don\rquote t think they go into sociology.  But it is remarkable that, it\rquote 
s probably nine or ten, depending on how you count them, that\rquote s quite high, it\rquote s nearly a tenth, and it\rquote s far more than there are people, for example, out of the whole of Humanities, there\rquote s only about thre
e people who appear to be straight humanitists.  Straight humanitists.  How would you classify Ivor Crewe? He\rquote s a social scientist, isn\rquote t he?  But if you do a hard line definition, there\rquote 
s very few ex-Professors of English, and why this would be, God only knows. I don\rquote t think that sociology gives you any great advantage in terms of interpersonal relationships.  And an awful lot of what I find I\rquote 
m currently doing, is to keep the stuff ticking over, is about interpersonal stuff.  You have to work with large numbers of people, and I don\rquote t mind doing that.  I find that\rquote s quite good.  And I think, if you don\rquote 
t want to work with large numbers of people, you shouldn\rquote t do this kind of job.  There are Vice-Chancellors who just only ever see the University Secretary, 
as far as I can see, and the University Secretary sees two people, and these two people see four people, and by about Thursday, Heads of Departments know what\rquote s on.  I\rquote 
d like to see them all the time.  Whether I could do that in a university on, say, the scale of Newcastle or Edinburgh, God only knows. There are other very straightforward things which people think are sociological, but I don\rquote 
t think are sociological at all \endash  a commitment to widening participation, a strong line on anti-racism and so on.  It\rquote 
s got some classic Left/Liberal concerns, and feeling that you can do something about it, that you have to stand up and be counted. I couldn\rquote t persuade fellow Principals in Scotland to make a statement supporting the Scottish Executives\rquote 
 line against fees, because, currently, we\rquote re forbidden.  The memorandum of Understanding I signed with the Scottish Funding Council, forbids me to charge fees. I\rquote m not allowed to charge fees.  I can\rquote 
t even debate it.  So I wanted them to say that we support the current posture.  \'93Oh!\'94 (LAUGHS)  \'93Bastards!  Get up!  Be counted!\'94  And it was almost, almost impossible, whereas I feel you can - \'93Oh, opposition, a political statement!\'94  
\'93Yes, yes!  A political statement!\'94  Whereas I would do those things and probably have, not i
n any particularly radical or particularly outspoken way, [but] I actually feel that you ought to do those things.  That people who have been relatively privileged and successful and [have] the confidence to do that, should do it. That\rquote 
s why I do say the things I say, without particularly organising, very effectively, so to do.  But I\rquote m not sure - an interest in widening access can\rquote 
t be, you know, the preserve of sociologists, it ought to be the preserves of everybody.  Although you can do things like, say, \'93Look, the post-code data\'94 \endash  bane of our lives - \'93is only a proxy for social class, and what we\rquote 
re talking about is social class.  And you can\rquote t use occupation, given the issue is poor households that are female-headed\'94. It\rquote s a wicked combination of occup
ational structure, poverty and household composition, and this is rather complicated. There is no simple fix.  The real issue at the moment \endash  particularly in great chunks of Scotland, about access to higher education \endash 
 is poverty in female-headed households, and even that isn\rquote t easy on post-codes, because it can be all over the place.  I don\rquote t think that\rquote 
s rocket science, but it may be only people who have handled more complex data sets might actually begin to say those sorts of things, or are still interes
ted in the distribution of resources.  But other people could easily say it.  Sociologists might be slightly more inclined to do that, but if I look at the interests of one or two of the others, other sociologists who are Heads of Institutions, they haven
\rquote t taken a great interest.  I mean, Janet Finch is really interested in Medical Education now, she pushes on in professions allied to medicine.  I don\rquote t actually see that she says much as a sociologist, as such.  So, anyway, enough?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117  No, no.  Just one or two concluding things.  So you\rquote ve done research, you\rquote ve done teaching, and you\rquote 
ve now run a university.  Do you feel any stronger attraction to any of the three, would you say?
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \ltrpar\s24\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid8917117 \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs20\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe2057\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp2057 {\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 COLIN:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 Well, I have said, and I might as well put on tape, that I have co
lleagues who really want to give up being a Head of Institution to go back to their research.  My predecessor, Andrew Miller, got himself what is called a Leverhulme Senior Fellowship, on concluding being Head of Stirling, to go back, literally, into his 
o
ld labs in the University of Edinburgh.  And really, what he wanted to do was to be relieved of all this, to go back to his research.  I find the only thing that attracts me is the thought of going to do a couple of years rather elementary teaching.  I ca
n\rquote 
t imagine going back to do research!  I can imagine going back to try and rise to the challenge of teaching Introductory Sociology. And probably, if I think about it seriously, I ought to think about doing it, not in a relatively privileged situation like
 Edinburgh, and giving it to them as a free gift, I would think of a more benighted spot, either in Britain or overseas, and think about making some contribution \endash  maybe India\rquote s the answer \endash 
 but go and teach it in some other context.  I would quite fancy doing that.  I mean literally teaching \endash  not administering teaching.  I don\rquote t mind running the course, I think take responsibility for the courses you run, but I don\rquote 
t want to go back to do quality assurance, or to manage the development of the curriculum, or something like this.  I\rquote d, literally, want to go back to be a lecture and seminar and classroom teacher.  Overall, yeah, it\rquote 
s amazing to get books out.  It\rquote s tremendous.  And I\rquote ve had a tremendous amount of friendship and companionship, and great to get papers accepted, and all of that, and it\rquote 
s great to get doctoral students finished and getting Ph. Ds. out the door.  But probably teaching.  And some of the administrative successes.  The Moray House merger, which I think is probably the best merger done
 in British higher education, the most successful, the most effective.  Nobody believed that could be done, and that was amazing.  There\rquote 
s no rules about how you do that, and I was given complete kind of freedom, and prised fourteen and a half million out 
of the Funding Council, at the end of it, to pay for some of it.  Again, as I told Sutherland, he could stop paying me, I just wanted ten per cent!  I didn\rquote t want a salary, I\rquote 
d just work on commission!  (LAUGHS)  But again, if it had been a consultant who had done it, they would have got that kind of money too - if Coopers Lybrand had managed that merger.  And I don\rquote 
t think a lot of that comes out of my sociology.  I think I\rquote ve done the sociology the way I did because I\rquote m the kind of person I am, perhaps, a
nd then went on to look after universities and departments in the same sort of way.  But a lot of it has not been very theorised or conscious.  I don\rquote t think I\rquote m, say, a natural, but I just do it in the same sort of way, and get on with it.

\par }\pard\plain \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid8917117 \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs20\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe2057\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp2057 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 Right.  Now, a completely different question, which is more to do with families and social mobility.  I\rquote 
d be interested to know what your four children have done, or are doing \endash  occupationally?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 COLIN:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 Oh, sure.  I\rquote ve got two from the first marriage, two from the second.  And the second two, it\rquote s easy, because they
\rquote re still at school.  So, there is not all that much to be said, with a slightly unexpected thing, that the elder of the two, Islay\'85 has a real aptitude for music\'85 And Catherine, who is only ten, is a is 
a little charmer.  The elder two, Rachel is easy\'85 She went to Manchester, did politics and geography, and got a 2:1, and did the exam to get into the fast stream of the Civil Service\'85
 and she waltzed into the fast stream of the Civil Service, and went in the Foreign Office.  She stayed three years in the Foreign Office. We then discovered something we didn\rquote 
t know, that the major accounting firms, as they are, go recruiting two or three years into the Civil Service\'85 So she moved to Leeds, and trained with Co
opers and Lybrand, who are looming surprisingly large on these tapes, and became an accountant in three years flat, and became an auditor\'85
 If you audit for a major company, eventually this other major company grabs you to face the auditors.  She moved from auditing Yorkshire Electricity \endash  then a Public Sector enterprise company \endash  to becoming an auditor }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid8917117 for }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 Yorkshire Electricity: she moved to Yorkshire Electricity.  Her real achievement was then she moved out of being an auditor, into general management in Y
orkshire Electricity, as they privatised.  Yorkshire Electricity is now a privatised utility company, and for a while, very satisfyingly, she managed Commercial Billing \endash  \'85 it was the 5,000 biggest customers that Yorkshire Electricity had 
\endash  with a vast army of part-time women. \'85
 Then Yorkshire Electricity gets taken by West Midlands or some German company.  Well, she and three or four others got themselves made redundant earlier this calendar year, and have set up an energy buying consultancy firm in Leeds,
 which advises other companies about energy futures.  They\rquote re all partners in this firm, and they make a large amount of money\'85 Luke\'85 didn\rquote t really settle terribly easily when we came back from Oz\'85
. He got out of his comprehensive school in Birmingham, to go to a sixth form college, and it wasn\rquote t terribly successful\'85
 He then went to the Tech, Matthew Boulton Tech.  [Finally, with the support of his grandmother, he went] to a crammer in Oxford\'85 He\rquote d already got an A in art.  And Luke never does the easy thin
gs.  He did physics and two maths at the crammers, and got straight A\rquote 
s.He had spotted the degree he wanted to do, which was Engineering Design, jointly between Glasgow University Faculty of Engineering and Glasgow College of Art, which is a rather good pl
ace to go  [He did tried the first year of this, but did not like it.  Finally he] found a course he really wanted to do: furniture design at what was\'85 the old High Wycombe Furniture School, the old mono tech, now part of Brunel\'85
 He did three years furniture making at Brunel, and got his degree\'85 By this time, he\rquote s living with [his girlfriend] Debbie.  They were into a kind of new life, Luke finished up in \'93The Life Foundation\'94
, which is a commune in North Wales.  Actually, he keeps the thing up, because he can actually re-hinge doors, and he\rquote s good at that sort of thing.  And New Life Foundation makes money, actually they train yoga trainers, and they\rquote 
ve got a whole series of non-pharmaceutical solutions to pain, in the broadest sense\'85 I went to a very interesting thing [on pain] in Lynwood, to see what it was like.  They do a lot of work with Down\rquote s Syndrome kids.  It\rquote 
s not that loss is particularly feminised, but it\rquote s felt in a particular way by women, and there are people who have lost husbands, children.  They do a lot of bereavement work, and they have ways of handling all this\'85 Luke makes, he\rquote 
s into greenwood furniture, he makes stuff that has not been dried, and he has as very neat line in meditation stools.  And you leave the Life Foundation with one o
f your souvenirs as one of these greenwood stools, which allows you not to have to quite get down on the ground! And he makes them and sells them!  He hung on in there for four or five years\'85
 [Most recently] the commune has split, has split several times.  [And Luke has been very unwell, and is now living with Jocelyn.]
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 Is Jocelyn working?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 COLIN:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 Yeah, no, Jocelyn\rquote 
s now just taken early retirement from Oxford Brookes. Her trajectory was that she got out of the classroom.  She was a classroom teacher
 at a primary school, but with a degree.  She did M.Eds. and then some research in Westfield College, which is now part of Birmingham University.  And because of the injunction there is on all initial teacher education, or initial teacher training provide
rs, to have }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid8917117 n}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117  per cent of people with recent classroom experience \endash  you have to have them, it\rquote s compulsory, otherwise you\rquote 
re not qualified to teach teachers \endash  she got one of the positions to teach primary, and she got into Oxford Brookes Education Departmen
t, which was part of Westminster College.  And she taught in there, and liked it very much.  But then, as part of the current rounds, about 18 months ago, another round of offers was on the table, and she decided she would take it.   So she\rquote 
s living in the same house in Oxford, apparently is busier than ever.  
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 
Colin, could I ask you one final question?  This really is the final one!  What would you say have been the worst and the best things in your life?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8917117\charrsid8917117 COLIN:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8917117 Oh, Christ!  I probably think worst, it would still be my father dying when I was 12. Probably.  I mean, it\rquote 
s still about the most painful and, I would have thought, probably the most life-changing thing that happened.  Although having thought about it, of course, I suspect I wouldn\rquote t have b
een the person I am, had he been there.  I think life might have been quite hard \endash  not financially \endash  I think it might have been quite a lot of straightforward clashing, and I think I wouldn\rquote 
t have had the freedom to become the person I actually am, which i
s slightly slightly more expansive and, I would have said, in some ways, more disorganised.  I think there would have been struggles about schooling, universities, and those sorts of things.  How can you anticipate, you know, if you\rquote 
re kind of a sub-adoles
cent when your father dies?  But still, in terms of the worst thing, probably, and because it was probably more devastating on my brother and sister, and my mother of course.  I still feel that.  Best?  I should think the second marriage is quite good.  A
nd I think the girls, I don\rquote t think there\rquote s anything wrong with Rachel, or even Luke, God help us.  But the second marriage, well, marriage isn\rquote 
t the important thing about it, we got quite a long way into it before we were married, but the girls, in particular.  Having the children the second time around, where poverty wasn\rquote 
t quite so grinding.  You realise, at the time, you can afford to eat meat now - it wasn\rquote t entirely clear you could then - that\rquote s good.  Both Islay and Catherine are extraordinary, and I like that.  And I like what we\rquote 
ve been able to do since we\rquote ve been in Scotland.  And Jan\rquote s pretty extraordinary as well. Workwise, I think it probably was getting the Chair at Edinburgh, because I was skidding, and it\rquote s not entirely clear where I was going
 at that time.  To suddenly get the chance of a major Chair in a major department in a major university, is extraordinary. That doesn\rquote t happen to many people, ever, and it\rquote 
s, you know, one of the better jobs in the country for someone like me, or the world probably.  And then that turned into a curious kind of opportunism, and that period\rquote s been pretty good.  I mean, it\rquote 
s not that I dislike what I am now, but I see what I\rquote m doing now as less remarkable than the step into the Chair. I suppose, in terms of the best things, the second marriage.  There\rquote 
s lots that was tremendously good about the first marriage, but, I think, you do learn from your mistakes, and things are actually quite \'85 I mean, I quite like the way it is, the way it is now, and the satisfactions, and we\rquote 
ve done, and have gone on doing quite interesting things.  Like we\rquote ve just bought another house, and things like that.  That\rquote s good. I now regret, not the age of the children, but that I can see retirement coming.  I don\rquote 
t, at the moment, want to stop.  I don\rquote t want to be like, well, the Brian Fenders of this world \endash  who I saw this morning \endash  because you\rquote re gathering loads and loads of work that\rquote 
s much the same as they were always doing before.  There\rquote s no need to do that.  I don\rquote t want to do that.  I would love to be viewing, instead of having just under five years at Stirling, I\rquote 
d like to think I had ten.  But I then, presume, would think about it slightly differently.  I\rquote d think, \'93Oh God, I\rquote ve got to get out of here, I can\rquote t bear it\'94.  But already, I feel it\rquote s too short.  I\rquote 
m horrified to discover I\rquote ll be off the payroll before the next RAE. Now that\rquote s rather sad, isn\rquote t it!  (LAUGHS)  Because I ought to say that\rquote s massive irresponsibility.  \'93Nothing to do with me, babies, I\rquote 
ll be long gone!\'94  But it\rquote s those, I think, probably.  I didn\rquote t even see, professionally, the devastations of Keith Joseph at Aston.  I\rquote 
d made myself redundant.  I could have stayed at Aston, but it was pretty horrid.  But in some ways, that was all exciting.  That was just what you would expect of the bastards.  It looked bad, but I don\rquote 
t think I experienced it, at the time, as badly as it probably ought to have been.  I mean, resilience or something?  But, I didn\rquote t see is quite as bad as that.  All right?
\par 
